{"title_page": "Francis Maude", "text_new": "{{for|the English recipient of the Victoria Cross|Francis Cornwallis Maude}}\n{{Short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Maude of Horsham\n|honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PC}}\n|image            = Francis Maude, Minister for the Cabinet Office.jpg\n|office           = [[Minister of State for Trade|Minister of State for Trade and Investment]]\n|primeminister    = [[David Cameron]]\n|term_start       = 11 May 2015\n|term_end         = 10 February 2016\n|predecessor      = [[Ian Livingston, Baron Livingston of Parkhead|The Lord Livingston of Parkhead]]\n|successor        = [[Mark Price, Baron Price|The Lord Price]]\n|office1          = [[Minister for the Cabinet Office]]<br>[[Paymaster General]]\n|primeminister1   = [[David Cameron]]\n|term_start1      = 12 May 2010\n|term_end1        = 11 May 2015\n|predecessor1     = [[Tessa Jowell]]\n|successor1       = [[Matthew Hancock|Matt Hancock]]\n|office2          = [[Chairman of the Conservative Party]]\n|leader2          = [[Michael Howard]]<br>[[David Cameron]]\n|term_start2     = 6 May 2005\n|term_end2        = 2 July 2007\n|predecessor2     = [[Liam Fox]]<br>[[Maurice Saatchi, Baron Saatchi|The Lord Saatchi]]\n|successor2       = [[Caroline Spelman]]\n{{Collapsed infobox section begin|Shadow Cabinet Positions <br> (1997-2010) {{nowrap|}}|titlestyle=border-top:solid 1pt #eee}}\n|office4          = [[Minister for the Cabinet Office|Shadow Minister for the Cabinet Office]]\n|leader4         = [[David Cameron]]\n|term_start4      = 2 July 2007\n|term_end4        = 11 May 2010\n|predecessor4     = [[Tim Collins (politician)|Tim Collins]] {{small|(2002)}}\n|successor4     = [[Tessa Jowell]]\n|office5         = [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster|Shadow Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]]\n|leader5         = [[David Cameron]]\n|term_start5      = 2 July 2007\n|term_end5        = 11 May 2010\n|predecessor5     = [[Oliver Heald]]\n|successor5      = ''Vacant''\n|office6          = [[Shadow Foreign Secretary]]\n|leader6          = [[William Hague]]\n|term_start6      = 2 February 2000\n|term_end6        = 18 September 2001\n|predecessor6     = [[John Maples]]\n|successor6       = [[Michael Ancram]]\n|office7          = [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer]]\n|leader7          = [[William Hague]]\n|term_start7      = 2 June 1998\n|term_end7        = 1 February 2000\n|predecessor7     = [[Peter Lilley]]\n|successor7       = [[Michael Portillo]]\n|office8          = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport]]\n|leader8          = [[William Hague]]\n|term_start8      = 11 June 1997\n|term_end8        = 2 June 1998\n|predecessor8     = [[Virginia Bottomley]]\n|successor8       = [[Peter Ainsworth]]{{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n{{Collapsed infobox section begin|Ministerial Positions <br> (1987-1992) {{nowrap|}}|titlestyle=border-top:solid 1pt #eee}}\n|office9          = [[Financial Secretary to the Treasury]]\n|primeminister9   = [[John Major]]\n|term_start9      = 28 November 1990\n|term_end9        = 11 April 1992\n|predecessor9     = [[Peter Lilley]]\n|successor9       = [[Stephen Dorrell]]\n|office10         = [[Minister of State for Europe]]\n|primeminister10  = [[Margaret Thatcher]]\n|term_start10     = 25 July 1989\n|term_end10       = 28 November 1990\n|predecessor10    = [[Lynda Chalker, Baroness Chalker of Wallasey|Lynda Chalker]]\n|successor10      = [[Tristan Garel-Jones]]\n|office11         = [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Trade and Industry]]\n|primeminister11  = [[Margaret Thatcher]]\n|term_start11     = 13 June 1987 \n|term_end11       = 26 July 1989\n|predecessor11    = [[Robert Atkins (politician)|Robert Atkins]]\n|successor11      = [[John Redwood]]{{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n{{Collapsed infobox section begin|Parliamentary Representation {{nowrap|}}|titlestyle=border-top:solid 1pt #eee}}\n|office12         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start12       = 26 May 2015<br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n|term_end12      =\n|office13         = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[Horsham (UK Parliament constituency)|Horsham]]\n|term_start13     = 1 May 1997\n|term_end13       = 30 March 2015\n|predecessor13    = [[Peter Hordern]]\n|successor13      = [[Jeremy Quin]]\n|office14         = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[North Warwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Warwickshire]]\n|term_start14     = 9 June 1983\n|term_end14       = 9 April 1992\n|predecessor14    = Constituency established\n|successor14      = [[Mike O'Brien (British politician)|Mike O'Brien]]\n{{Collapsed infobox section end}}\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1953|7|4|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Abingdon-on-Thames]], [[Berkshire]], England\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|spouse           = {{marriage|Christina Hadfield|1984}}\n|children         = 5\n|alma_mater       = [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]<br>[[University of Law]]\n|website          = {{url|francismaude.com|Official website}}\n}}\n'''Francis Anthony Aylmer Maude, Baron Maude of Horsham''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|PC}} (born 4 July 1953) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[politician]], who served over 25 years on the [[Frontbencher|front bench]] in the House of Commons,<ref name= \"resignation\"/> including posts as [[Minister for the Cabinet Office]] and [[Paymaster-General]], as well as [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Member of Parliament]] representing [[Horsham (UK Parliament constituency)|Horsham]] in [[Sussex]], and then as '''Baron Maude of Horsham''' as [[Minister of State]] for Trade and Investment until April 2016.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |title=Economy Lead {{!}} Francis Maude to be Trade Minister at Foreign Office and BISEconomy Lead |url=http://www.economylead.com/international/francis-maude-to-be-trade-minister-at-foreign-office-and-bis-71563 |website=www.economylead.com |access-date=20 February 2016}}</ref> He now runs his own consultancy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fmapartners.co.uk/about|title=Francis Maude Associates Partners Limited|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Abingdon School, Abingdon, Oxfordshire, England-23April2011.jpg|thumb|left|120px|[[Abingdon School]]]]\nMaude is the son of [[Angus Maude]] (1912\u20131993), a life peer and one-time Conservative cabinet minister. He spent part of his childhood in Sydney, Australia, while his father edited the ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]''. On the family's return to the UK, he was educated at [[Abingdon School]], at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], and at the [[University of Law|College of Law]]. He was [[Call to the Bar|called to the Bar]] at the [[Inner Temple]] in 1977, and practised criminal law.\n\nHe served as a member of [[Westminster City Council]] from 1978 to 1984.\n\n==Political career==\n\n===In government, 1983\u20131992===\nMaude was first elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] to represent the constituency of [[North Warwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Warwickshire]] in the Conservative Party's landslide victory at the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 general election]]. In 1984, he became the [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the [[Minister of State|Minister]] for Employment [[Peter Morrison]]. Maude then became an assistant government [[whip (politics)|whip]] (1985\u201387) and Minister for Corporate and Consumer Affairs (1987\u201389), then part of the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|DTI]]. A Thatcherite, Maude was appointed in 1989 the [[Minister for Europe]] in the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] to spearhead the policy outlined in the [[Bruges Group (United Kingdom)|Bruges Speech]], attacking the [[Delors Commission|Delors Plan]] in order to exclude Britain from an economic and political Union of Europe. In 1992 he acted as deputy for [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[Norman Lamont]] and was one of the two UK signatories to the [[Maastricht Treaty]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/cf373d1a-0c53-11e1-8ac6-00144feabdc0|title=Subscribe to read {{!}} Financial Times|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\nMaude was one of the first \"men in grey suits\" to hold discussions with [[Margaret Thatcher]] in November 1990 after she failed to win the first round of a [[1990 Conservative Party (UK) leadership election|leadership election]]. He told Thatcher that he would support her as long as she went on, but he did not believe she could win the leadership contest.<ref>{{cite news|title=Falling from power: Cabinet overboard (memoirs extract)|url=http://www.margaretthatcher.org/commentary/displaydocument.asp?docid=109189|publisher=Margaret Thatcher Foundation|accessdate =16 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[John Major]] became [[Prime Minister]], Maude was made the [[Financial Secretary to the Treasury]]. However, in the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]] he lost his seat to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] candidate, [[Mike O'Brien (UK politician)|Mike O'Brien]], and was thus forced to vacate his ministerial roles. According to [[Daniel Finkelstein]] of ''[[The Times]]'' the loss came as a 'terrible blow' to Maude; all his peers had managed to cling on and were together forming a government. In the [[1992 Dissolution Honours|Dissolution Honours that year]], he was made a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52943 |date=5 June 1992 |page=2  |supp=y}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2006 interview, Maude stated that the introduction of [[Section 28]] legislation whilst he was in Government (which banned Councils from promoting homosexuality and led to the closure of gay support groups) was \"a mistake\", adding it might have even contributed to the [[AIDS]] death of his brother Charles, who was homosexual, among others.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tory Chairman: Gay policies were wrong|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-448.html#|newspaper=Pink News|date=9 February 2006|accessdate=12 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629085109/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-448.html|archive-date=29 June 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2012 he expanded further on his views on [[Section 28]], saying \"in hindsight, it was very wrong \u2014 very wrong. It was a legislative provision that came out of honourable motives. It took me some time to realise what an emblem of intolerance Section 28 had become for gay people. It was the tip of a deep iceberg \u2014 the iceberg below the surface being a host of anti-gay social attitudes.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/mother-tongue/9150056/Francis-Maude-My-brothers-Aids-death-transformed-my-views-on-gay-marriage.html |title=Francis Maude: My brother's Aids death transformed my views on gay marriage|author= Patrick Sawer|work=Daily Telegraph|date=17 March 2012|accessdate=23 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Out of Parliament, 1992\u20131997===\nOut of [[Parliament]] after the 1992 general election, Maude began a series of business roles. He worked in banking as managing director at [[Morgan Stanley]] from 1993 to 1997. He was also appointed a non-executive director of [[Asda|ASDA Group Plc]] in July 1992, and served as a director of [[Salomon Brothers]] from 1992 to 1993. He also chaired the government's Deregulation Task Force from 1994 to 1997. This was preparation as Cabinet Office Minister from 2010, when he was required to highlight areas of expenditure where savings could be made from streamlining the delivery and implementation of policy goals.\n\n===Shadow Cabinet, 1997\u20132010===\nIn the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] Maude was elected MP for [[Horsham (UK Parliament constituency)|Horsham]]. Almost immediately he was re-appointed to the Conservative [[front bench]], now the [[Official Opposition (United Kingdom)|opposition]] in Parliament. He served as Shadow [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport]], Shadow [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], and Shadow [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] until 2001.\n\nMaude managed [[Michael Portillo]]'s unsuccessful bid for the Conservative leadership in 2001, after which he declined a front bench role under the new Party Leader [[Iain Duncan Smith]]. He was considered to be a 'moderniser' and on the centre-left of the party, writing in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' (24 June 2002), he said that the Conservative Party's electoral problems had been caused by its failure to \"look and sound like modern Britain\". [[Norman Tebbit]]'s secretary, Beryl Goldsmith, criticised Maude after this, asking:{{quote|How many male, white, straight Conservative MPs currently passionately campaigning for the selection of more women, and more men and women from ethnic minorities, would voluntarily relinquish their own seats in order to encourage local associations to follow the policy line they preach from their own smug, safe base? Precious few I would guess \u2013 including The Hon. Francis Maude.}} Outside the Shadow Cabinet, Maude founded Conservatives for Change, ''CChange'', becoming its first [[chairman]]. ''CChange'' was designed to promote the modernisation of the Conservative Party. Around the same point he also founded [[Policy Exchange]].\n\nAfter the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], Maude returned to the Shadow Cabinet as [[Chairman of the Conservative Party]]. As the so-called Holy Spirit of Conservative modernisation, Maude set the Tory Party on the path to reform which saw David Cameron selected as Party Leader. In his first speech to the Conservative Conference as Party Chairman, Maude presented what he calls his \"killer slide\". The slide revealed that \"voters confronted with the party\u2019s immigration policy neutrally supported it by two to one, but when told that it was a Conservative policy the proportions reversed\". The point he was making was not that sound conservative ideas damaged the Conservative Party but that 'The Conservative Party, as it was then seen, was damaging good Conservative policies\". During his tenure, alongside newly elected Leader David Cameron, the Conservatives adopted the [[A-List (Conservative)|A-List]] of [[Prospective parliamentary candidate|parliamentary candidate]]s, with priority being given to women and people from ethnic minorities.\n\nIn July 2007, Maude was made Shadow Cabinet Office Minister and Shadow [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]], with responsibility for preparing the Conservatives for government, with some dubbing him the Party's \"enforcer\". At the Conservative Party Conference in October 2007 he said: \"David (Cameron) has asked me to lead an implementation team that will ensure that we are as well-prepared as any incoming government has ever been. Our priorities rigorously sorted. Our teams armed with the knowledge and capabilities that will enable new ministers to start making a difference from day one.\" Ahead of the 2010 general election, Maude led attempts by the then-Conservative Opposition to work with the UK Civil Service to prepare for government.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/2518435/Civil-servants-preparing-for-Conservative-Government-with-secret-meetings.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Robert | last=Winnett | title=Civil servants 'preparing for Conservative Government' with secret meetings | date=7 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nMaude supported [[Republican Party (US)|Republican]] [[John McCain]] in the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 U.S. Presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Convention fever: MPs fly in hoping to find prescription for success|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article4583484.ece|work=The Times |location=London |date=22 August 2008|accessdate=12 September 2008|first1=Tom|last1=Baldwin|first2=Siobhan|last2=Kennedy}}</ref> He led the Conservative Party delegation to the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]].\n\n===Return to Government, 2010\u20132016===\n[[File:Francis Maude.jpg|thumb|left|Maude in the [[Cabinet Office]] in 2013]]\nMaude was appointed [[Paymaster General]] and [[Minister for the Cabinet Office]], with the right to attend Cabinet, on 12 May 2010, following the formation of the [[Conservative\u2013Liberal Democrat coalition agreement|Conservative\u2013Liberal Democrat Coalition]]. As Cabinet Office Minister, Maude was [https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm130619/debtext/130619-0001.htm#13061976001073 responsible] for: public service efficiency and reform groups, [[Civil Service (United Kingdom)|Civil Service]] issues, [[industrial relations]] strategy in the [[public sector]], [[transparency (behavior)|transparency]], [[Civil Contingencies Secretariat|civil contingencies]], [[civil society]] and [[cyber-security]].\n\n====Efficiency and Reform====\n\nIn 2010 Maude set up the [[Efficiency and Reform Group]] (ERG), in the [[Cabinet Office]] to work with [[HM Treasury]] with the aim of making government departments more efficient. This [https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/efficiency-and-reform-group%20 work] includes stopping wasteful spending; improving the way government buys goods and services; reducing losses from fraud, error and debt; raising money by selling empty buildings and underused properties; and reviewing and reshaping large scale projects.\n\nSavings are difficult to measure, but the work of ERG claims to have contributed to \u00a33.75 billion of savings in 2010\u201311, \u00a35.5 billion in 2011-12 and an \"unprecedented\" \u00a310 billion in 2012\u201313. ERG claims to achieve savings of at least \u00a320 billion in the financial year 2014 to 2015. Cumulatively, by 2015 Maude had delivered more than \u00a350 billion of audited savings during the Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centreforpublicimpact.org/3603-francis-maude/|title=Francis Maude: Shaking up the UK\u2019s status quo|accessdate=7 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThese savings included [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303215147/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-saves-10-billion-for-taxpayers%20 include] \u00a33.4 billion by reducing the size of the Civil Service and reforming Civil Service pensions; \u00a33.8 billion by linking together departments to buy goods and services and enforcing controls on recruitment and use of consultants; and \u00a30.6 billion by exiting 500,000 square metres of property.  In December 2014 Francis Maude set out plans to make a further \u00a310 billion of efficiency savings between 2017 and 2018 and an additional \u00a315 to \u00a320 billion for 2019 to 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/efficiency-and-reform-in-the-next-parliament|title=Efficiency and reform in the next Parliament|author=|date=|work=www.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\n====Civil Service reform====\nIn June 2012 Maude laid out his [http://my.civilservice.gov.uk/reform/the-reform-plan/ plans] for reforming the Civil Service. The Reform programme was endorsed by leadership of the Civil Service, the Cabinet Secretary and Head of the Civil Service. The document laid out a series of practical actions including steps to improve the skills, abilities and performance of civil servants; introduce a sharper performance management system; create a modern employment offer for staff; improve IT and flexible working across departments; and tighten the delivery of major projects. A year after the publication of the initial plan, Maude updated Parliament with a One Year On document, setting out successes and failures. This document included various further steps: establishing the principle of Extended Ministerial Offices, and introducing Functional Leadership across Whitehall. However, in November 2013, former [[Cabinet Secretary (United Kingdom)|Cabinet secretary]] [[Lord Butler of Brockwell]] told the BBC that \"Mr Maude and some of his colleagues don't understand leadership.\"<ref name= brock>{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25163208|title=Francis Maude criticised over leadership by Lord Butler|work=BBC News:Politics|date=30 November 2013 |accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> Butler said the relationship between ministers and the Civil Service worked best when there was loyalty on both side and public criticism showed something was wrong. A spokesman for Maude said good leadership required issues to be addressed, not swept under the carpet.<ref name= brock/>\n\n====Transparency====\nMaude oversaw the Government's groundbreaking transparency policy. This work includes making sure that departments include specific open data commitments in their business plans, regularly publishing open data sets on all central and local government spending over \u00a325,000, senior staff salary details and how the government is performing against objectives. [[Data.gov.uk]] contains over 9,000 datasets including local crime statistics, sentencing rates, hospital infection rates and GP performance.\n\nMaude also led the UK Government's work with the [[Open Government Partnership]]. This work helped make the British government the most open in the world at the time, and led directly to the creation of services such as the [[Citymapper]] app and challenger banks like [[Monzo (bank)|Monzo]].<ref>Cameron, David (2019). For the Record. United Kingdom: William Collins. p. 213. {{ISBN|0-008-23928-2}}.</ref>\n\nFollowing Maude's reforms the United Nations rated the UK government as the most open in world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publicadministration.un.org/egovkb/en-us/Reports/UN-E-Government-Survey-2016|title=UN E-Government Survey 2016|accessdate=7 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Government Digital Service and Gov.uk====\nMaude was responsible for the creation of the [[Government Digital Service]], with the aim to consolidate internal IT and replace government 1,700 various websites with a single web hub, [[gov.uk]]. The new consolidated website won Design of the Year 2013 at the [[Design Museum]] awards, beating [[The Shard]] and the [[2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympics cauldron]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wainwright|first=Oliver|title='Direct and well-mannered' government website named design of the year|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2013/apr/16/government-website-design-of-year|accessdate=16 April 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=16 April 2013}}</ref> Its revolutionary single source model inspired government websites around the world, including in the United States, New Zealand and Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/sprint-14-speech-by-francis-maude |title=Sprint 14|accessdate=7 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centreforpublicimpact.org/3603-francis-maude/|title=Francis Maude: Shaking up the UK\u2019s status quo|accessdate=7 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Government Digital Strategy also committed Departments to redesigning all existing government services that serve more than 100,000 users each year. Maude's office estimated that moving services from offline to digital channels could save approximately \u00a31.8 billion a year; at the time digital transactions cost 20 pence each compared to \u00a33 for a phone call and \u00a37 for a physical letter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://publications.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/digital/strategy/#what-the-strategy-is-about%20|title=Government Digital Strategy|author=|date=|work=cabinetoffice.gov.uk}}</ref><ref>Cameron, David (2019). For the Record. United Kingdom: William Collins. p. 213. {{ISBN|0-008-23928-2}}.</ref>\nIn June 2014 Maude warned that elderly people would have to apply for key benefits including [[Carer's Allowance]] online. His remarks were criticized by organizations who work with the elderly partly on the grounds that poorer people may not be able to afford computer facilities and, partly because even computer literate people may lose their skills in old age. Whilst critics estimated that over 5 million pensioners have never used the internet, Maude said that 'refuseniks' could be offered a one-off lesson.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/internet/10889563/Go-on-the-internet-or-lose-access-to-government-services-Francis-Maude-tells-pensioners.html#disqus_thread|title=Go on the internet - or lose access to government services, Francis Maude tells pensioners|author= Christopher Hope|work=Daily Telegraph|date=10 June 2014|accessdate=10 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==== Elevation to the Lords ====\nIn February 2015, Maude announced he would be standing down at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|general election]] three months later. Following the election, on 14 May 2015 Maude was elevated to the House of Lords and he was created, by [[letters patent]], '''Baron Maude''' of Horsham, of [[Shipley, West Sussex|Shipley]] in the [[West Sussex|County of West Sussex]] on 26 May 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Crown Office notice|url = https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/2340660|website = London Gazette|access-date = 19 February 2016|publisher = HM Government|date = 29 May 2015|series = State notices}}</ref> This allowed him to be appointed as [[Minister of State]] for Trade and Investment jointly at the [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills]] and the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]], replacing [[Ian Livingston, Baron Livingston of Parkhead|the Lord Livingston of Parkhead]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Nine months later, Maude announced his resignation from this post on 10 February 2016, to be replaced by [[Mark Price, Baron Price|Mark Price]].<ref name=\"resignation\">{{cite web|title=Lord Maude resignation letter|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/lord-maude-resignation-letter-and-pms-response|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career outside of Parliament: 2016\u2013present==\n\nSince leaving his role as Minister for Trade and Investment in March 2016, Maude has begun a number of new business roles, including serving as an advisory board member at [[OakNorth Bank]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/07/31/oaknorth-bank-set-to-hire-lord-francis-maude/|title=Oaknorth Bank set to hire Lord Francis Maude|newspaper=The Telegraph|access-date=5 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/09/12/ex-trade-minister-francis-maude-says-british-firms-not-lazy-but/|title=Ex-trade minister Francis Maude says British firms not lazy but 'too comfortable'|newspaper=The Telegraph|access-date=5 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bdaily.co.uk/entrepreneurship/26-09-2016/1474837473-this-months-london-appointments/|title=This month's London appointments|last=Wood|first=Billy|newspaper=Bdaily Business News|access-date=5 January 2017}}</ref> which deals with business and property finance, and specialises in supporting the UK's growth businesses since September 2016. He has been an advisory board member at Anvest Partners,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/maude-lord-minister-for-trade-and-investment-acoba-recommendation/summary-of-business-appointments-applications-rt-hon-lord-maude-of-horsham|title=Summary of business appointments applications - Rt Hon Lord Maude of Horsham - GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|access-date=5 January 2017}}</ref> a real estate investment company since May 2016, and a Senior Adviser with Covington & Burling LLP,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prweek.com/article/1411664/lord-francis-maude-appointed-covington-senior-advisor-public-policy|title=Lord Francis Maude appointed by Covington as senior advisor for public policy {{!}} PR Week|website=www.prweek.com|access-date=5 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/oct/11/ex-minister-francis-maude-takes-brexit-advisory-job-at-law-firm|title=Ex-minister Francis Maude takes Brexit advisory job at law firm|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|date=11 October 2016|last2=Weaver|first2=Matthew|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=5 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/event/europe-crossroads-impact-brexit-trump-presidency-and-member-state-elections-doing|title=Europe at a Crossroads? The Impact of Brexit, the Trump Presidency, and Member State Elections on Doing Business in the EU {{!}} The National Law Review|website=www.natlawreview.com|access-date=5 January 2017}}</ref> a business and corporate law firm since November 2016. He has also been a [[Non executive chairman|Non Executive Chairman]] at Cogent Elliott Group Ltd,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thedrum.com/news/2016/10/04/cogent-brings-former-bray-leino-chief-bruce-hutton-group-ceo-and-francis-maude-non|title=Cogent brings in former Bray Leino chief Bruce Hutton as group CEO and Francis Maude as non-exec|website=The Drum|access-date=5 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gorkana.com/2016/10/cogent-elliott-appoints-hutton-as-ceo/|title=Cogent Elliott appoints Hutton as CEO - Gorkana|date=17 October 2016|newspaper=Gorkana|language=en-US|access-date=5 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/business/francis-maude-joins-communications-agency-11978215|title=Tory politician joins board of comms agency|last=Jones|first=Tamlyn|date=5 October 2016|newspaper=birminghammail|access-date=5 January 2017}}</ref> an advertising agency, since November 2016.\n\nMaude's primary occupation since leaving politics is his role as the co-founder and chairman of [https://www.fmapartners.co.uk/ Francis Maude Associates Partners], which he runs with his former special advisor [[Simone Finn]], Baroness Finn. It is a consulting firm specialising in government efficiency and reform around the world, with its work based on Maude's experience as Minister for the Cabinet Office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fmapartners.co.uk/about|title=Francis Maude Associates Partners Limited|access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n[[File:Francis Maude World Economic Forum 2013.jpg|thumb|right|Maude attending the Davos [[World Economic Forum]] in 2013]]\nMaude was reported in [[Alan Clark]]'s [[Alan Clark Diaries|''Diaries'']] supporting the view that it would be impolitic for the Conservative Party to appoint the ''Jewish'' then-Chancellor of the Exchequer [[Nigel Lawson]] as Foreign Secretary.<ref>Diaries, Alan Clark, p185</ref> He has since praised the Conservative Party for appointing a man \"born into a Jewish family\" as [[Prime Minister]], referring to [[Benjamin Disraeli]].\n\nWhile in the Shadow Cabinet Maude was accused of hypocrisy by promoting a \"family-friendly\" image while being the non-executive chairman of Jubilee Investment Trust plc, which held 21% of American pornographic actress [[Jill Kelly (actress)|Jill Kelly]]'s adult DVD business,<ref>{{cite news |title=Tory Chief and the Porn Star |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/tory-chief-and-the-porn-star-643911 |work=Daily Mirror |date=2 October 2006 |accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref> and chairman of the Mission Marketing Group, which has advertised for [[WKD Original Vodka|WKD]] drinks and [[Playboy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pendennis|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/may/13/francismaude.olivermarre|work=The Observer |location=London |date=13 May 2007|accessdate=12 September 2008|first=Oliver|last=Marre}}</ref> Maude, \"who has railed against irresponsible lending by banks and mortgage companies\", was accused of hypocrisy for receiving more than \u00a3100,000 as a director of a company that has profited from [[sub-prime]] mortgages. His annual salary was \u00a325,000 from 2002 to 2005, for attending around six meetings a year for the company, and \u00a312,000 a year 2006 to 2008. The company went into [[liquidation]] in April 2009.<ref>''The Observer'' 3 May 2009</ref>\n\nMaude faced criticism during the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|expenses scandal]]. However the Legg Report made no complaint against him and found that he had \"no issues\".<ref name=leg>{{cite web|date=4 February 2010|title=Review of past ACA payments|last=|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmselect/cmmemest/348/348.pdf|publisher=House of Commons Members Estimate Committee|doi=|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref> ''The Daily Telegraph'' had argued that: two years after the Fees Office rejected a claim for mortgage interest on Maude's Sussex home, Maude purchased a flat in London, close to another house he already owned. He rented out the London house and claimed \u00a335,000 mortgage interest on this flat.<ref>{{cite news|last=Winnett|first=Robert|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5305293/David-Camerons-shadow-cabinet-drawn-into-expenses-scandal-MPs-expenses.html|title=David Cameron's shadow cabinet drawn into expenses scandal (11 May 2009)|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date= 10 May 2009|accessdate=13 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring a discussion on ''[[Newsnight]]'' on 22 October 2010 Maude noted that ministerial salaries had been reduced by 5% under the new Government. He was accused of comparing this cut to the 'pain' suffered by Britain's poor.<ref>Samira Shackle, Stephanie Hegarty and [[George Eaton (journalist)|George Eaton]] [http://www.newstatesman.com/uk-politics/2009/10/oxford-universitywealth-school \"The new ruling class\"] ''New Statesman'', 1 October 2009</ref>\n\nMaude supports the \"[[Big Society]]\", but says that his work as an MP is a sufficient contribution to it.<ref>[http://audioboo.fm/boos/155599-eddie-mair-putting-francis-maude-on-the-spot-what-volunteering-do-you-do ''Radio 4''] Eddie Mair [42m:52s]: And what volunteering do you do?</ref> Maude argued that like most people he was doing things which could be defined as \"volunteering with a capital V\" but are part of being \"an active citizen in an active community\".\n\n===Fuel crisis===\n\nOn 28 March 2012, during the [[2012 United Kingdom fuel crisis]], Maude \"foolishly\" advised people to fill up their vehicles and to store fuel in garages in [[jerrycan]]s.<ref name=competence>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/9177146/Theres-a-crisis-of-competence-at-the-top-of-the-Tory-party.html|title=There's a crisis of competence at the top of the Tory party|author=Iain Martin|date=31 March 2012|work=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=1 September 2012|location=London}}</ref> His remarks were widely criticised, queues up to half a mile long formed outside [[petrol station]]s<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/energy/fuel/9174755/David-Cameron-accused-of-presiding-over-shambles-on-fuel-as-panic-buying-gets-worse.html|title=David Cameron accused of presiding over 'shambles' on fuel as panic buying gets worse|author=Gordon Rayner|work=Daily Telegraph|date=28 March 2012|accessdate=1 September 2012|location=London}}</ref> and petrol retailers criticised the Government for causing panic.<ref name=createacris>{{cite news|author=Rowena Mason|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/energy/fuel/9171458/Petrol-retailers-Government-intent-on-creating-fuel-crisis.html |title=Petrol retailers: Government intent on creating fuel crisis |work=Daily Telegraph |date=28 March 2012 |accessdate=16 August 2012 |location=London}}</ref> Matt Wrack, General Secretary of the [[Fire Brigades Union]] pointed out Maude's advice was dangerous and illegal, and could be disastrous in the event of a fire.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/fuel-strike-francis-maude-fuels-crisis-with-jerry-can-blunder-7594476.html|title=Fuel strike: Francis Maude fuels crisis with 'jerry can' blunder|author=Miranda Bryant|newspaper=Evening Standard|date=28 March 2012|accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref> Brian Madderson, the petrol chairman of the Retail Motor Industry Federation said that the Government appeared to be \"intent on creating a crisis out of a serious concern and that drivers should ignore \"dangerous advice\". Maude denied that it would increase the risk of explosions, however the following day Transport Minister [[Mike Penning]], a former firefighter, confirmed the advice was wrong, saying he didn't think Maude understood how big jerrycans were.<ref name=mikep>{{cite news|title=Fuel strike threat:Maude's jerrycan advice a mistake|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-17545258|work=BBC News|date=29 March 2012 |accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref> On 30 March 2012, the Labour Peer [[Toby Harris, Baron Harris of Haringey|the Lord Harris]] called for Maude's resignation,<ref name=Toby>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/energy/fuel/9175292/Fuel-strike-anger-over-government-advice-grows-as-woman-burnt-in-petrol-accident.html|title=Fuel strike anger over government advice grows as woman is burnt in petrol accident|author=Donna Bowater|work= Daily Telegraph|date=30 March 2012|accessdate=1 September 2012|location=London}}</ref> after a woman suffered severe burns during an attempt to decant petrol next to a lit gas cooker. Harris believed that Maude's advice helped cause the incident.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/maude-urged-to-quit-over-tanker-driver-strike-row-as-woman-suffers-burns-7602990.html |title=Maude urged to quit over tanker driver strike row as woman suffers burns |work=The Independent |date=30 March 2012|accessdate=16 August 2012 |location=London |first=Rob |last=Williams}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMaude married Christina Jane Hadfield in 1984, and they have five children. He was on the governing body of [[Abingdon School]] from 1988-2006 and was Chairman of the Governors from 1995\u20132003.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/uploads/school/files/abingdonian/2004_Michaelmas_V023_N005.pdf#page=4|title=Headmasters Foreword|publisher=The Abingdonian}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Old Abingdonians]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050607062308/http://www.francismaude.com/ Francis Maude MP] ''official constituency website''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050422054303/http://www.conservatives.com/tile.do?def=people.person.page&personID=4857 Profile] at the Conservative Party\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = francis-maude/115 | hansard = mr-francis-maude | hansardcurr = 1750 | guardian = 3429/francis-maude | publicwhip = Francis_Maude | theywork = francis_maude | record = Francis-Maude/Horsham/326 | bbc = 25444.stm | journalisted = francis-maude }}\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/222.stm Profile: Francis Maude] ''BBC News'', 10 February 2005\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br>for [[North Warwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Warwickshire]]|years=[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013[[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mike O'Brien (British politician)|Mike O'Brien]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Hordern]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br>for [[Horsham (UK Parliament constituency)|Horsham]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jeremy Quin]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lynda Chalker, Baroness Chalker of Wallasey|Lynda Chalker]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of 