{"title_page": "John Marek", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = John Marek\n| image        =\n| imagesize    = 150px\n| office       = [[Presiding Officer of the National Assembly for Wales|Deputy Presiding Officer of the Welsh Assembly]]\n| term_start   = 2 May 2000\n| term_end     = 7 May 2007\n| predecessor  = [[Jane Davidson]]\n| successor    = [[Rosemary Butler (politician)|Rosemary Butler]]\n| office2      = [[Member of the Welsh Assembly]] <br /> for [[Wrexham (Assembly constituency)|Wrexham]]\n| assembly2    = \n| majority2    = \n| term_start2  = 6 May 1999\n| term_end2    = 3 May 2007\n| predecessor2 = ''Assembly Established''\n| successor2   = [[Lesley Griffiths]]\n| office3      = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham]]\n| parliament3  = \n| majority3    = \n| term_start3  = 9 June 1983\n| term_end3    = 14 May 2001\n| predecessor3 = [[Tom Ellis (politician)|Tom Ellis]]\n| successor3   = [[Ian Lucas]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1940|12|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[London]], England\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| restingplace = \n| birthname    = \n| nationality  = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| party        = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| otherparty   = [[Forward Wales]] (2003\u201310) <br /> [[John Marek Independent Party|John Marek Independent]] (2003) <br /> [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (1983\u20132003)\n| spouse       = \n| relations    = \n| children     = \n| residence    = \n| alma_mater   = [[King's College London]]\n| occupation   = \n| profession   = \n| cabinet      = \n| committees   = \n| portfolio    = \n| religion     = \n| signature    = \n| signature_alt= \n| website      = \n| footnotes    = \n}}\n'''John Marek''' (born 24 December 1940), is a [[Wales|Welsh]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician, former [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] and former Member of the [[National Assembly for Wales]]. He was leader of [[Forward Wales]] until joining the Conservatives in 2010.<ref name=\"BBC290310\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/8592783.stm |title=Former Wrexham Labour MP and AM John Marek joins Tories|publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=29 March 2010|accessdate=26 May 2017  }}</ref>\n\nHe was [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Member of Parliament for [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham]] from 1983 until 2001. He stood down after he was elected to represent [[Wrexham (Assembly constituency)|Wrexham]] in the [[National Assembly for Wales]] in 1999. This was initially for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], but he was deselected in 2003 and formed Forward Wales, for whom he was re-elected. He was defeated at the [[2007 National Assembly for Wales election|2007 election]].\n\n==Background==\nBorn in London of [[Czech lands|Czech]] descent, Marek was the only [[Czech language|Czech]]-speaking Member of the [[UK Parliament]].<ref name=\"BBC010999\">{{cite web | title=AMs profile: John Marek | publisher=BBC News | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/uk/wales/13126.stm |date=1 September 1999|accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref> He was educated at [[Chatham House Grammar School]] and at [[King's College London]] where he earned a BSc in Mathematics in 1962, and a PhD in Mathematics in 1965. He became a lecturer in applied mathematics at [[Aberystwyth University]]\n\n==Political career==\nMarek was elected a member of Ceredigion District Council in 1979 and served until 1983; he was chair of its finance sub-committee in the year 1982\u201383.\n\nHaving previously unsuccessfully contested [[Ludlow (UK Parliament constituency)|Ludlow]] in [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974]], Marek was elected as [[Wales Labour Party|Labour Party]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for the [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham Westminster constituency]] in [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] and served as a party spokesman on Treasury matters, although he was not offered a government post in 1997.<ref name=\"BBC010999\"/>\n\nAs a supporter of devolution, he chose to move to the [[National Assembly for Wales]] in 1999, and stood down from the UK Parliament in 2001. In the Assembly he became increasingly known as a maverick. In 2000, he was elected as Deputy [[Presiding Officer of the National Assembly for Wales|Presiding Officer]] against the candidate preferred by the Labour leadership. This move, and his frequent criticisms of the Labour-led [[Wrexham (county borough)|Wrexham County Borough]] led to his deselection as the Labour Party's candidate for the National Assembly elections of 1 May 2003.<ref>{{cite news | title=AM loses reselection battle | publisher=BBC News | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/2780445.stm | date=22 February 2003|accessdate=2003-02-22}}</ref>\n\nMarek then stood as a candidate for the [[John Marek Independent Party]] and defeated the official Labour Party candidate, [[Lesley Griffiths]], a former secretary of his, by 973 votes. Later that year he formed a new political party called [[Forward Wales]]' ({{lang-cy|Cymru Ymlaen}}).<ref>{{cite news  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/north_east/2984637.stm | title=Marek is first independent AM | publisher=BBC Wales  | date=2 May 2003|accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref> He ran for re-election in the [[2007 National Assembly for Wales election|2007 Welsh Assembly election]], but was defeated by Labour's Lesley Griffiths by 1,250 votes, thanks to a swing to the Conservatives, [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], and [[United Kingdom Independence Party|UKIP]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Independent John Marek is ousted | publisher=BBC News | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/north_east/6622221.stm | date=4 May 2007 |accessdate=4 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March 2010, Marek joined the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]],<ref name=\"BBC290310\"/> and he was later confirmed as the party's candidate for the [[2011 National Assembly for Wales election|2011 Welsh Assembly election]] where he again came second to Griffiths, by 3,335 votes in the [[Wrexham (Assembly constituency)|Wrexham constituency]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Ex-Wrexham MP and AM John Marek to fight seat as Tory | publisher=BBC News | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-east-wales-10851946| accessdate=3 August 2010 | date=3 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/election2011/constituency/html/26703.stm | title = Election 2011 - Wales - Wrexham | publisher = [[BBC News]]  | date = 5 June 2011 | accessdate = 4 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Wrexham AFC==\nIn 2006 he was appointed a vice president of [[Wrexham A.F.C.]] by new owners Nev Dickens and Geoff Moss, and remained a vice president until the club passed into the ownership of the Wrexham Supporters Trust.\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | dr-john-marek | John Marek }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham]]\n  | years  = [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013[[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]\n  | before = [[Tom Ellis (politician)|Tom Ellis]]\n  | after  = [[Ian Lucas]]\n}}\n{{s-par|wal}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Members of the National Assembly for Wales|Assembly Member]] for [[Wrexham (Assembly constituency)|Wrexham]]\n  | years  = [[1999 National Assembly for Wales election|1999]]\u2013[[2007 National Assembly for Wales election|2007]]\n  | before = ''New post''\n  | after  = [[Lesley Griffiths]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Presiding Officer of the National Assembly for Wales|Deputy Presiding Officer]]\n  | years  = 2000\u20132007\n  | before=[[Jane Davidson]]\n  | after=[[Rosemary Butler (politician)|Rosemary Butler]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marek, John}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Welsh Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Politics of Wrexham]]\n[[Category:Independent politicians in Wales]]\n[[Category:Wales AMs 1999\u20132003]]\n[[Category:Wales AMs 2003\u20132007]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Wales]]\n[[Category:National Union of Railwaymen-sponsored MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:Academics of Aberystwyth University]]\n[[Category:People educated at Chatham House Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) politicians]]\n[[Category:English people of Czech descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = John Marek\n| image        =\n| imagesize    = 150px\n| office       = [[Presiding Officer of the National Assembly for Wales|Deputy Presiding Officer of the Welsh Assembly]]\n| term_start   = 2 May 2000\n| term_end     = 7 May 2007\n| predecessor  = [[Jane Davidson]]\n| successor    = [[Rosemary Butler (politician)|Rosemary Butler]]\n| office2      = [[Member of the Welsh Assembly]] <br /> for [[Wrexham (Assembly constituency)|Wrexham]]\n| assembly2    = \n| majority2    = \n| term_start2  = 6 May 1999\n| term_end2    = 3 May 2007\n| predecessor2 = ''Assembly Established''\n| successor2   = [[Lesley Griffiths]]\n| office3      = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham]]\n| parliament3  = \n| majority3    = \n| term_start3  = 9 June 1983\n| term_end3    = 14 May 2001\n| predecessor3 = [[Tom Ellis (politician)|Tom Ellis]]\n| successor3   = [[Ian Lucas]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1940|12|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[London]], England\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| restingplace = \n| birthname    = \n| nationality  = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| party        = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| otherparty   = [[Forward Wales]] (2003\u201310) <br /> [[John Marek Independent Party|John Marek Independent]] (2003) <br /> [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (1983\u20132003)\n| spouse       = \n| relations    = \n| children     = \n| residence    = \n| alma_mater   = [[King's College London]]\n| occupation   = \n| profession   = \n| cabinet      = \n| committees   = \n| portfolio    = \n| religion     = \n| signature    = \n| signature_alt= \n| website      = \n| footnotes    = \n}}\n'''John Marek''' (born 24 December 1940), is a [[Wales|Welsh]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician, former [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] and former Member of the [[National Assembly for Wales]]. He was leader of [[Forward Wales]] until joining the Conservatives in 2010.<ref name=\"BBC290310\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/8592783.stm |title=Former Wrexham Labour MP and AM John Marek joins Tories|publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=29 March 2010|accessdate=26 May 2017  }}</ref>\n\nHe was [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Member of Parliament for [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham]] from 1983 until 2001. He stood down after he was elected to represent [[Wrexham (Assembly constituency)|Wrexham]] in the [[National Assembly for Wales]] in 1999. This was initially for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], but he was deselected in 2003 and formed Forward Wales, for whom he was re-elected. He was defeated at the [[2007 National Assembly for Wales election|2007 election]].\n\n==Background==\nBorn in London of [[Czech lands|Czech]] descent, Marek was the only [[Czech language|Czech]]-speaking Member of the [[UK Parliament]].<ref name=\"BBC010999\">{{cite web | title=AMs profile: John Marek | publisher=BBC News | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/uk/wales/13126.stm |date=1 September 1999|accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref> He was educated at [[Chatham House Grammar School]] and at [[King's College London]] where he earned a BSc in Mathematics in 1962, and a PhD in Mathematics in 1965. He became a lecturer in applied mathematics at [[Aberystwyth University]]\n\n==Political career==\nMarek was elected a member of Ceredigion District Council in 1979 and served until 1983; he was chair of its finance sub-committee in the year 1982-83.\n\nHaving previously unsuccessfully contested [[Ludlow (UK Parliament constituency)|Ludlow]] in [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974]], Marek was elected as [[Wales Labour Party|Labour Party]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for the [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham Westminster constituency]] in [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] and served as a party spokesman on Treasury matters, although he was not offered a government post in 1997.<ref name=\"BBC010999\"/>\n\nAs a supporter of devolution, he chose to move to the [[National Assembly for Wales]] in 1999, and stood down from the UK Parliament in 2001. In the Assembly he became increasingly known as a maverick. In 2000, he was elected as Deputy [[Presiding Officer of the National Assembly for Wales|Presiding Officer]] against the candidate preferred by the Labour leadership. This move, and his frequent criticisms of the Labour-led [[Wrexham (county borough)|Wrexham County Borough]] led to his deselection as the Labour Party's candidate for the National Assembly elections of 1 May 2003.<ref>{{cite news | title=AM loses reselection battle | publisher=BBC News | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/2780445.stm | date=22 February 2003|accessdate=2003-02-22}}</ref>\n\nMarek then stood as a candidate for the [[John Marek Independent Party]] and defeated the official Labour Party candidate, [[Lesley Griffiths]], a former secretary of his, by 973 votes. Later that year he formed a new political party called [[Forward Wales]]' ({{lang-cy|Cymru Ymlaen}}).<ref>{{cite news  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/north_east/2984637.stm | title=Marek is first independent AM | publisher=BBC Wales  | date=2 May 2003|accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref> He ran for re-election in the [[2007 National Assembly for Wales election|2007 Welsh Assembly election]], but was defeated by Labour's Lesley Griffiths by 1,250 votes, thanks to a swing to the Conservatives, [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], and [[United Kingdom Independence Party|UKIP]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Independent John Marek is ousted | publisher=BBC News | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/north_east/6622221.stm | date=4 May 2007 |accessdate=4 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March 2010, Marek joined the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]],<ref name=\"BBC290310\"/> and he was later confirmed as the party's candidate for the [[2011 National Assembly for Wales election|2011 Welsh Assembly election]] where he again came second to Griffiths, by 3,335 votes in the [[Wrexham (Assembly constituency)|Wrexham constituency]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Ex-Wrexham MP and AM John Marek to fight seat as Tory | publisher=BBC News | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-east-wales-10851946| accessdate=3 August 2010 | date=3 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/special/election2011/constituency/html/26703.stm | title = Election 2011 - Wales - Wrexham | publisher = [[BBC News]]  | date = 5 June 2011 | accessdate = 4 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Wrexham AFC==\nIn 2006 he was appointed a vice president of [[Wrexham A.F.C.]] by new owners Nev Dickens and Geoff Moss, and remained a vice president until the club passed into the ownership of the Wrexham Supporters Trust.\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | dr-john-marek | John Marek }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham]]\n  | years  = [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013[[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]\n  | before = [[Tom Ellis (politician)|Tom Ellis]]\n  | after  = [[Ian Lucas]]\n}}\n{{s-par|wal}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Members of the National Assembly for Wales|Assembly Member]] for [[Wrexham (Assembly constituency)|Wrexham]]\n  | years  = [[1999 National Assembly for Wales election|1999]]\u2013[[2007 National Assembly for Wales election|2007]]\n  | before = ''New post''\n  | after  = [[Lesley Griffiths]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Presiding Officer of the National Assembly for Wales|Deputy Presiding Officer]]\n  | years  = 2000\u20132007\n  | before=[[Jane Davidson]]\n  | after=[[Rosemary Butler (politician)|Rosemary Butler]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marek, John}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Welsh Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Politics of Wrexham]]\n[[Category:Independent politicians in Wales]]\n[[Category:Wales AMs 1999\u20132003]]\n[[Category:Wales AMs 2003\u20132007]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Wales]]\n[[Category:National Union of Railwaymen-sponsored MPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:Academics of Aberystwyth University]]\n[[Category:People educated at Chatham House Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) politicians]]\n[[Category:English people of Czech descent]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1982-83 \u2192 1982\u201383", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Marek"}
{"title_page": "Donato Mancini", "text_new": "'''Donato Mancini''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] poet.<ref name=windsorstar>[https://windsorstar.com/news/local-news/mancini-debuts-as-universty-of-windsor-writer-in-residence \"Mancini debuts as University of Windsor writer-in-residence\"]. ''[[Windsor Star]]'', September 28, 2017.</ref> He is most noted for his 2017 collection ''Same Diff'', which was a shortlisted [[Griffin Poetry Prize]] finalist in 2018.<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/omni/billy-ray-belcourt-aisha-sasha-john-and-donato-mancini-shortlisted-for-the-griffin-poetry-prize/ \"Billy-Ray Belcourt, Aisha Sasha John, and Donato Mancini shortlisted for the Griffin Poetry Prize\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', April 10, 2018.</ref>\n\nHe has also been a two-time [[ReLit Awards|ReLit Award]] nominee for his poetry collections ''Ligatures'' in 2006 and ''\u00c6thel'' in 2008.\n\nOriginally from [[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]], [[Ontario]],<ref name=windsorstar/> he is a graduate of the [[University of British Columbia]].<ref name=windsorstar/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mancini, Donato}}\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male poets]]\n[[Category:Canadian literary critics]]\n[[Category:People from Burlington, Ontario]]\n[[Category:University of British Columbia alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Canada-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Donato Mancini''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] poet.<ref name=windsorstar>[https://windsorstar.com/news/local-news/mancini-debuts-as-universty-of-windsor-writer-in-residence \"Mancini debuts as University of Windsor writer-in-residence\"]. ''[[Windsor Star]]'', September 28, 2017.</ref> He is most noted for his 2017 collection ''Same Diff'', which was a shortlisted [[Griffin Poetry Prize]] finalist in 2018.<ref>[https://quillandquire.com/omni/billy-ray-belcourt-aisha-sasha-john-and-donato-mancini-shortlisted-for-the-griffin-poetry-prize/ \"Billy-Ray Belcourt, Aisha Sasha John, and Donato Mancini shortlisted for the Griffin Poetry Prize\"]. ''[[Quill & Quire]]'', April 10, 2018.</ref>\n\nHe has also been a two-time [[ReLit Awards|ReLit Award]] nominee for his poetry collections ''Ligatures'' in 2006 and ''\u00c6thel'' in 2008.\n\nOriginally from [[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]], [[Ontario]],<ref name=windsorstar/> he is a graduate of the [[University of British Columbia]].<ref name=windsorstar/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mancini, Donato}}\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male poets]]\n[[Category:Canadian literary critics]]\n[[Category:People from Burlington, Ontario]]\n[[Category:University of British Columbia alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Canada-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donato_Mancini"}
{"title_page": "Edward Leigh", "text_new": "{{Other people}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Sir Edward Leigh\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]] \n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image            = Official portrait of Rt Hon Sir Edward Leigh MP crop 2.jpg\n| office           = [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Chairman of the <br /> Public Accounts Committee]]\n| term_start       = 7 June 2001\n| term_end         = 9 June 2010\n| preceded         = [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]]\n| succeeded        = [[Margaret Hodge|Dame Margaret Hodge]]\n| office1          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Gainsborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Gainsborough]]<br /><small>[[Gainsborough and Horncastle (UK Parliament constituency)|Gainsborough and Horncastle]] (1983\u20131997)</small>\n| majority1        = 22,967 (45.0%)\n| term_start1      = 9 June 1983\n| term_end1        =  \n| predecessor1     = [[Marcus Kimball]]\n| successor1       = \n| birth_name       = Edward Julian Egerton Leigh\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1950|07|20|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Metropolitan Borough of Kensington|Kensington]], [[London]], England\n| spouse           = Mary ''n\u00e9e'' Goodman <br />(''now'' Lady Leigh)\n| party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| children         = 6\n| residence        = London and Lincolnshire\n| alma_mater       = [[Durham University]]\n| occupation       = [[Politician]]\n| profession       = [[Barrister]]\n| website          = [http://www.edwardleigh.org.uk/ www.edwardleigh.org.uk]}}\n\n'''Sir Edward Julian Egerton Leigh''' (born 20 July 1950) is a [[British people|British]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician who has served as a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] since 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gainsboroughconservatives.org.uk/people/sir-edward-leigh|title=Rt Hon Sir Edward Leigh MP|publisher=Gainsborough Conservatives|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nLeigh has represented [[Gainsborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Gainsborough]], [[Lincolnshire]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] since [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] (representing its predecessor [[List of United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|constituency]], [[Gainsborough and Horncastle (UK Parliament constituency)|Gainsborough and Horncastle]], until [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]])<ref>{{cite web|publisher=UK Parliament Website|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/edward-leigh/25183|title=Edward Leigh profile|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020192116/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/edward-leigh/25183|archivedate=20 October 2012}}</ref> and has spoken in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliament]] on [[civil liberties]], [[constitutional]], [[ecclesiastical]] and [[economic]] matters.\n\nLeigh was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the [[2013 Birthday Honours|Queen's 2013 Birthday Honours]] for \"public and political service\",<ref name=gaz31712>{{London Gazette|issue=60534 |supp=y |page=1|date=15 June 2013}}</ref><ref name='HM Birthday Honours 2013'>{{cite web | url = https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/206698/Birthday_Honours_List_2013.pdf | title = Birthday Honours List 2013 | accessdate = 14 June 2013 | date = 14 June 2013 | publisher = HM Government}}</ref> and has also received [[honour]]s from the [[French Government|French]] and [[Italian Government]]s.\n\nInitially dubbed \"[[Viscount|the Viscount]]\" in [[Houses of Parliament|parliamentary circles]] alluding to his [[landed gentry]] [[ancestry|background]], Leigh has a reputation at [[Westminster]] for his independence of mind as a \"serial rebeller\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/eureferendum/11973490/David-Cameron-sparks-MPs-protests-in-the-Commons-by-sacking-three-serial-Tory-rebels-from-Europe-body.html|title=David Cameron sparks MPs' protests in the Commons by sacking three 'serial' Tory rebels from Europe body|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=29 July 2017}}</ref> who is prepared to vote against his own [[political party]] if it conflicts with his own principles.<ref name=\"conservativehome.blogs.com\">{{cite web|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/platform/2013/06/edward-leigh-mp.html|title=Sir Edward Leigh MP: After a weak Queen's Speech, we could lose the next election - unless we change course|publisher=}}</ref> He was one of the original [[Maastricht Rebels]] and reportedly got the sack for organising Euro-rebels among ministers.<ref name=\"conservativehome.blogs.com\"/> In 2003 Leigh opposed military intervention in Iraq;<ref name=\"Did your MP support the rebels\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2862397.stm|location=London, UK|work=The BBC|title=Did your MP support the rebels?|date=19 March 2003}}</ref> he has since called for those who voted for the [[Iraq War]], and are still seeking to justify their support for it, to be held to account.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cornerstonegroup.wordpress.com/2016/07/14/on-the-chilcot-report/|title=On the Chilcot Report|last=cornerstonegroup|date=14 July 2016|website=Cornerstone|accessdate=29 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe served as the [[Chairman]] of the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] from 2001 to 2010, investigating government waste and seeking value for money in [[public expenditure]]. Sir Edward stepped down at the end of the [[parliamentary session]] in [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]], it being customary for an [[Her Majesty's Most Loyal Opposition (United Kingdom)|opposition MP]] to hold this post.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fm-world.co.uk/news/fm-industry-news/leigh-to-step-down-as-head-of-pac/|title=Leigh to step down as head of PAC|date=26 October 2009|work=FM World}}</ref>\n\nLeigh has edited and authored three books: ''Right Thinking'' (1988); ''The Nation that forgot God'' (2008);<ref>{{cite book|title=The Nation That Forgot God: A Book of Essays|last=Leigh|first=Edward|date=31 March 2008|publisher=Social Affairs Unit|isbn=9781904863410|editor-last=Haydon|editor-first=Alex|location=London}}</ref> and ''Monastery of the Mind'' (2012).<ref>{{cite book|title=Monastery of the Mind: A Pilgrimage with St Ignatius|last=Leigh|first=Sir Edward|date=31 July 2012|publisher=St Pauls Publishing|isbn=9780854398133}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Knights Bachelor Insignia.png|thumb|left|100px| Insignia of a [[Knight Bachelor]]]]\nLeigh was educated at [[The Oratory School]], the [[Lyc\u00e9e Fran\u00e7ais Charles de Gaulle]] (the French School in London) before going up to [[University College, Durham]], where he read [[History]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]]) and was elected President of the [[Durham Union Society]].\n\nAfter graduating Leigh was [[called to the Bar]] at the [[Inner Temple]] and practised in [[arbitration]] and [[criminal law]] at [[Chambers (law)|Goldsmiths Chambers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldsmithchambers.com/about-us/|title=About Us - Goldsmith Chambers|publisher=}}</ref> He is a [[Fellow]] of the [[Chartered Institute of Arbitrators]] (FCIArb) and formerly served as an [[Ensign (rank)|Ensign]] in the [[Honourable Artillery Company]].<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm130717/debtext/130717-0002.htm#13071772001774 Profile], publications.parliament.uk; accessed 14 July 2015.</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHis father, [[Neville Leigh|Sir Neville Leigh]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCVO}}, hailed from the [[History of Cheshire|ancient Cheshire]] [[Dynasty|family]] of [[High Legh#History|West Hall, High Legh]], a descendant of the [[Egerton family#Earls of Bridgewater (1617)|Egertons, earls of Bridgewater]].\n\nHis maternal grandfather was [[Colonel]] Cyril Denzil Branch {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MC}}, a French citizen, and he is a nephew of [[Russian nobility|Prince]] [[Galitzine|Nikolai Galitzine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://burkespeerage.com/|title=Burke's Peerage - The Official Website|website=burkespeerage.com|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nLeigh first stood for Parliament at the [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974 general election]] when he contested the safe [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] seat of [[Middlesbrough (UK Parliament constituency)|Middlesbrough]], but he was beaten by [[Arthur Bottomley]].\n\nLeigh worked in the private office of [[Margaret Thatcher]] from 1976\u201377 as a political secretary when she was Leader of the Opposition. Leigh was elected to [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames|Richmond Borough Council]] and thereafter to the [[Greater London Council]], serving as [[Councillor]] between 1974 and 1981.\n\nIn 1983, he was returned as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] for Gainsborough and Horncastle. A strong supporter of [[Margaret Thatcher]], Leigh visited [[10 Downing Street]] with fellow MP [[Michael Brown (UK politician)|Michael Brown]] on the morning of Thatcher's resignation as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] in 1990 to try to persuade her to carry on.<ref name=\"Blundell2008\">{{cite book|author=John Blundell|title=Lady Thatcher: A Portrait|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hbyeLS83iEIC&pg=PA163|accessdate=23 November 2012|date=September 2008|publisher=Algora Publishing|isbn=978-0-87586-631-4|pages=162\u2013163}}</ref> Although [[Charles Powell]] advised them it was a forlorn task, they were nonetheless granted access to [[Cabinet (government)|the Cabinet]] which was in process at the time. Leigh and Brown departed 10 Downing Street and walked down [[Whitehall]] back to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] reputedly with \"tears in their eyes\". After Thatcher resigned, in the ensuing leadership election, Leigh supported [[Michael Heseltine]], under whom he had served at the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] (DTI), preferring to support someone who had stabbed Thatcher in the front to those who had stabbed her in the back.<ref name=\"Criddle2012\">{{cite book|author=Byron Criddle|title=Almanac of British Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bDtm2o0m7gIC&pg=PA385|accessdate=23 November 2012|date=10 September 2012|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-26833-2|pages=385}}</ref>\n\nLeigh served as a [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] in [[John Major]]'s [[Major ministry (disambiguation)|ministry]]<!--intentional link to DAB page, 1990-93--> but was sacked in May 1993 over the stance he took by opposing the [[Maastricht Treaty]]. Whilst in office at the DTI he was a keen advocate of [[privatisation]] of the [[Post Office]] (opposed by Labour at the time but as the [[Royal Mail]] division attracting general bipartisan support and floated on the [[London Stock Exchange]] in 2013). In the following [[1995 Conservative Party (UK) leadership election|Conservative leadership election]], Leigh supported [[John Redwood]].<ref name=\"Criddle2012\"/>\n\nFrom 2001 until 2010, Leigh served as [[Chairman]] of the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]], the principal parliamentary body auditing the Budget, investigating government waste and seeking value for money in public expenditure. During his two terms as [[Parliamentary procedure|Chairman]], the PAC took evidence on 420 separate government projects and programmes and was responsible for saving the taxpayer over \u00a34 billion.<ref>'[http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/uk_news/Society/article252950.ece An open letter to my successor as Chair of the Committee of Public Accounts]', by Edward Leigh MP, March 2010</ref>{{better source|reason=This is a statement from Leigh himself |date=September 2019}}\n\nIn October 2006, Leigh was vocal in stating that after [[David Cameron]] had become leader of the party, core supporters were drifting away from voting Conservative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/oct/02/comment.politics|title=Max Hastings: Cameron's big problem - the Conservative party|first=Max|last=Hastings|date=1 October 2006|publisher=}}</ref> Nonetheless, his effective chairmanship of the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] led to the rejuvenation of his parliamentary career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/telegraph-view/10013176/An-artful-game-by-the-taxpayers-champion.html|title=An artful game by the taxpayers' champion|first=|last=|date=23 April 2013|accessdate=31 October 2019|newspaper=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 2008, as Chairman of the PAC, he was embarrassed by relying on flawed [[Department for Transport]] (DfT) statistics to attack motorcyclists for [[tax evasion]]. He accused 38% of motorcyclists of evading [[vehicle excise duty]]. He later apologised for this following the admission by the DfT that 95.5% of motorcycles are entirely legal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7268854.stm|title=MPs apologise for motorbike error|date=28 February 2008|work=BBC News Online|publisher=BBC|accessdate=15 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nLeigh was President of the socially conservative [[Cornerstone Group]] representing the views of over 40 Conservative Members of Parliament and was author of the group's inaugural pamphlet ''Faith, Flag and Family'' in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tory Catholic seeks to return 'faith, flag and family' to heart of party philosophy|url=http://archive.catholicherald.co.uk/article/29th-july-2005/3/tory-catholic-seeks-to-returnfaith-flag-and-family|newspaper=Catholic Herald|date=29 July 2005|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 to 2011, Leigh served as an Independent Financial Advisor to [[HM Treasury]], appointed by [[George Osborne]] to bring external challenge to the development and implementation of a new financial management strategy for central government. He stood down in 2011, but was then reappointed to report directly to the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] on improving Parliament's financial scrutiny of the Budget. He was a member of the Treasury Financial Reporting & Advisory Board and, in 2010, Leigh became a delegate to the [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]], speaking regularly and serving on the [[European Parliament Committee on Culture and Education|Culture, Science, Education and Media Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edwardleigh.org.uk/tags/council-of-europe/|title=Council of Europe - Edward Leigh MP - Gainsborough|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of 2010 Leigh was offered but declined the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[ambassadorship]] to the [[Holy See]].<ref>''The Daily Telegraph''. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/8246963/Criticism-as-David-Cameron-sends-trouble-shooter-to-the-Vatican.html Leigh turns down appointment as UK Ambassador to The Vatican]</ref> Leigh also supported [[Boris Johnson]]'s call to [[George Osborne]] in 2011 for lowering the rate of [[taxation]] in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] so as to assist its economic recovery following the [[credit crunch]].<ref>''The Evening Standard'': [http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23918264-boris-johnson-urges-george-osborne-over-lower-taxes.do Leigh joins call for lower taxes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201024842/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23918264-boris-johnson-urges-george-osborne-over-lower-taxes.do |date=1 February 2011 }}</ref> Leigh, a qualified [[barrister]] and an [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe|Assembly Member]] of the [[Council of Europe]],<ref>{{cite web|title=PACE Member File Edward Leigh|url=http://www.assembly.coe.int/nw/xml/AssemblyList/MP-Details-EN.asp?MemberID=6670|website=www.assembly.coe.int|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref> opposes further human rights legislation, as proposed by the [[European Court of Human Rights]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/columnists/charlesmoore/8333820/If-we-want-our-human-rights-then-bring-them-back-home.html# \"If we want our human rights then bring them back home\"], Telegraph.co.uk; accessed 14 July 2015.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Leigh was appointed [[Chairman]] of the [[Public Accounts Commission]], the body which audits the [[National Audit Office (United Kingdom)|National Audit Office]].\n\nIn 2012, Leigh, together with a record number of fellow Conservative MPs, including numerous [[Privy Counsellor]]s, successfully voted against the [[United Kingdom coalition government (2010\u20132015)|Coalition Government]]'s attempted railroading of [[House of Lords Reform Bill 2012|House of Lords]] [[Lords Reform|Reform]] by limiting time for meaningful parliamentary debate on this major constitutional issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/pm-pledges-one-more-try-at-lords-reform-10476236|title= PM pledges one more try at Lords reform|publisher= news.sky.com|date=11 July 2012|accessdate= 14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Leigh criticised the Government's decision to allow [[Mitochondrial disease#Management and prevention|mitochondrial replacement therapy]] to prevent the birth of the children with incurable diseases such as muscular dystrophy. These diseases affect up to 1 in 6,500 babies which Leigh stated could lead to people being \u201charvested for their parts\" and a divide between what he referred to as \"the modified and the unmodified\". The [[Department for Health]] asserted no genetic modification is involved.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/11069117/Britain-will-be-considered-a-rogue-state-if-it-creates-GM-people-MP-warns.html|title=Britain will be considered a 'rogue state' if it creates GM people, MP warns|author=Press Association|work=Daily Telegraph|date=1 September 2014|accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande|French President]] appointed him to the [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]] for his role as \u201ca bridge between our parliaments, our governments and our societies\u201d, as stated by [[Sylvie Bermann|H.E. Sylvie Bermann]] at his investiture.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ambafrance-uk.org/Sir-Edward-Leigh-is-made-an-Officier-in-the-Legion-d-Honneur|title=Sir Edward Leigh is made an Officier in the L\u00e9gion d'Honneur|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, he joined three other Conservative MPs in \"talking out\" a Bill introduced by [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] [[Caroline Lucas|Dr Caroline Lucas]], which aimed to reverse moves to privatise the [[NHS]]. By [[filibustering]] for three and a half hours, Lucas was left with just 17 minutes to present her Bill, which was subsequently shelved without a vote.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/nhs-reinstatement-bill-tory-mps-filibuster-debate-by-talking-about-deporting-foreigners-for-hours-a6925781.html NHS Reinstatement Bill: Tory MPs filibuster debate by talking about deporting foreigners for hours]. ''The Independent''. Published 11 March 2016. Retrieved 3 November 2017.</ref>\n\nOne of 21 MPs who, in March 2019, voted against LGBT inclusive sex and relationship education in English schools,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/education/lgbt-sex-relationship-education-mps-support/|title=MPs vote for LGBT inclusive sex and relationship education from primary school|first=Benjamin|last=Butterworth|date=28 March 2019|website=inews.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/21-mps-who-voted-against-14198149|title=21 MPs who voted against teaching kids about gay families|first=Nicola|last=Bartlett|date=28 March 2019|website=mirror}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://commonsvotes.digiminster.com/Divisions/Details/650#noes|title=Draft Relationships Education, Relationships and Sex Education and Health Education (England) Regulations 2019 - CommonsVotes|website=commonsvotes.digiminster.com}}</ref> Leigh was returned with a massive majority at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].<ref>[https://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/news/local-news/general-election-gainsborough-edward-leigh-3638105 www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk]</ref>\n\n===Beliefs===\nLeigh is a [[Roman Catholic]], and maintains a personal blog containing ''Thoughts from a Christian perspective''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://anothercountry.edwardleigh.org.uk/|title=Another Country &#124; Thoughts from a Christian perspective \u2014 by Edward Leigh|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref> He has argued for tightening of [[abortion law]] regarding [[Embryonic stem cell|human embryonic]] [[research]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/mps-throw-out-bids-to-reduce-abortion-limit-831577.html|title=MPs throw out bids to reduce abortion limit|date=20 May 2008|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/10/09/tory-mp-abortion-female-foetus_n_4071551.html|title=The Most Dangerous Position In Britain Today Is... 'To Be A Female Foetus'|date=9 October 2013|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/may/19/health.health|title=Ban on hybrid embryos and saviour siblings fails|first=Andrew|last=Sparrow|date=19 May 2008|publisher=}}</ref> He was on the losing side in defence of [[Section 28]] and opposed the [[Civil Partnership Act 2004]], voting against it in Parliament at its [[Reading (legislature)|Second Reading]]. Leigh later proposed an amendment to extend the property and pension rights afforded by [[civil partnership]]s to siblings who had lived together for more than 12 years. This was opposed by many backers of the initial [[Bill (law)|Bill]], such as fellow Conservative MP [[Alan Duncan|Sir Alan Duncan]], who dubbed it a [[wrecking amendment]].<ref name='ePolitix 2004-11-09'>{{cite web|url=http://www.epolitix.com/latestnews/article-detail/newsarticle/conservatives-split-on-civil-partnerships/?no_cache=1 |title=Conservatives split on civil partnerships |accessdate=13 January 2010 |last=Davie |first=Edward |date=9 November 2004 |publisher=ePolitix.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604180419/http://www.epolitix.com/latestnews/article-detail/newsarticle/conservatives-split-on-civil-partnerships/?no_cache=1 |archivedate=4 June 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name='Changing Attitude'>{{cite web|url=http://www.changingattitude.org.uk/news/newsitem.asp?id=72|title=Civil Partnership bill wrecking amendment defeated|last=Coward|first=Colin|date=9 November 2004|publisher=Changing Attitude|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070607205416/http://www.changingattitude.org.uk/news/newsitem.asp?id=72|archivedate=7 June 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Opposition to Conservative leadership===\nOn a number of occasions Leigh has voted against the leadership of his [[political party|party]] where it conflicts with his personal [[principle]]s.<ref name=\"conservativehome.blogs.com\"/> In 2003, Leigh rebelled against the leadership of his own party and the Labour government to \n[[Opposition to the Iraq War|oppose military intervention in Iraq]] in 2003.<ref name=\"Did your MP support the rebels\"/> He was one of only 15 Conservative rebels who opposed it at the time.\n\nSince the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 European Union Referendum]], Leigh advocates [[Brexit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|title=Which Tory MPs back Brexit, who doesn't and who is still on the fence? - Coffee House|date=16 February 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, the House of Commons overwhelmingly passed an Opposition motion to delay the introduction of [[Universal Credit]] and iron out problems with the system first. Leigh strongly criticised the Government decision to ignore the vote, stating: \"the road to tyranny is paved by executives ignoring parliaments.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/oct/19/were-not-ignoring-you-but-vote-doesnt-bind-pms-deputy-tells-mps We're not ignoring you but vote doesn't bind, PM's deputy tells MPs] ''[[The Guardian]]'' 19 October 2017</ref>\n\n===Speakership elections===\nA veteran [[backbencher]], Leigh was encouraged to run for the [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speakership of the House of Commons]], and after the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] for one of the [[Chairman of Ways and Means|Deputy Speakerships]], but chose not to stand then as [[Constitutional convention (political custom)|parliamentary convention]] was that governing party members were not to be elected to such offices unless already ''[[in situ]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/EdwardLeighMP/status/1121367417509351424|title=When a vacancy occurs I intend to stand for the office of Speaker. I would be a traditional Speaker who does not speak much. Like a judge I would, by my conduct and dress, submerge my personality into the office.|last=MP|first=Sir Edward Leigh|date=25 April 2019|website=@EdwardLeighMP|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/news/local-news/sir-edward-leigh-reveals-wants-2796354|title=Sir Edward Leigh says he wants to replace Bercow and become Speaker|last=Lodge|first=Matthew|date=25 April 2019|website=lincolnshirelive|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nLeigh ran for the Speakership of the House of Commons in [[2019 Speaker of the British House of Commons election|2019]] after Speaker [[John Bercow]] retired; he stated that, if elected Speaker, he would be fair to all sides and assume a traditional role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/politics/opinion/house-commons/106453/sir-edward-leigh-if-elected-speaker-i-would-submerge|title=Sir Edward Leigh: If elected Speaker, I would submerge my personality into the office and keep business flowing|date=11 September 2019|website=PoliticsHome.com|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref> He was eliminated after receiving 12 votes in the first ballot.\n\n===All-Party Parliamentary Groups===\nFluent in [[French language|French]], Leigh currently serves as Chairman of the [[All-party parliamentary group|All-Party Parliamentary Group]] on [[France]] and the [[All-party parliamentary group|All-Party Parliamentary Group]] on [[Italy]], delivering a speech in [[Italian language|Italian]] at the [[Palace of Westminster]] to visiting [[Chamber of Deputies (Italy)|Deputies of the Italian Parliament]]. He is also the Chairman of the new [[All-party parliamentary group|All-Party Parliamentary Group]] on [[Russia]], Secretary of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on [[Insurance]], and Chairman of the Foreign Affairs, Defence, and International Development subcommittee of the [[1922 Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/sir-edward-leigh/345|title=Rt Hon Sir Edward Leigh MP|website=UK Parliament|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nLeigh was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in [[2013 Birthday Honours|2013]] for \"public and political service\",<ref name=gaz31712/><ref name='HM Birthday Honours 2013'/>\n* [[Image:Knight-Bachelor.ribbon.png|45px]] [[Knight Bachelor]] (2013)\n* [[File:Legion Honneur Officier ribbon.svg|45px]] [[Officer|Officier]] of the [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]] (2015)\n* [[File:StellaItalia-Cav.png|45px]] [[Commander (order)|Commander]] of the [[Order of the Star of Italy]] (2017)\n* [[File:SMOM-gc.svg|45px]] [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Knight of Honour and Devotion]] of the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta]] (1994)\n* [[File:Royal Arms of the United Kingdom (Privy Council).svg|45px]] [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellor]] ([[2019 New Year Honours|2019]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/privy-council-appointments-december-2018|title=Privy Council appointments December 2018|website=GOV.UK}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLeigh married Mary Goodman in London on 25 September 1984 in London; the great granddaughter of [[Duke Georg Alexander of Mecklenburg-Strelitz]] through her mother, and the great-granddaughter of [[Lady Ottoline Morrell]] through her father. She is a direct descendant of [[Catherine II, Empress of Russia]] and [[Princess Augusta of Great Britain]], a sister of [[George III of the United Kingdom|King George III]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britroyals.com/succession.htm|title=Line of Succession to the British Throne|publisher=}}</ref> By marrying a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]], Lady Leigh had previously forfeited her precedence in the [[line of succession to the British throne]] until the [[Succession to the Crown Act 2013|change in the law of 2013]].\n\nSir Edward and Lady Leigh have six children (Natalia, Tamara, Benedict, Marina, Nicholas, and Theodore) and divide their time between homes in [[Westminster]] and in his [[Lincolnshire]] constituency. Their three eldest children work for [[HM Government]] as [[Her Majesty's Civil Service|civil servants]].\n\nLeigh suffers from [[rosacea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm131204/halltext/131204h0001.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 04 Dec 2013 (pt 0001)|website=publications.parliament.uk|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of MPs elected in the 1983 United Kingdom general election]]\n* [[List of Durham University people]]\n* [[:Category:Presidents of the Durham Union|List of Presidents of the Durham Union]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Edward Leigh}}\n* [http://www.edwardleigh.org.uk/ Sir Edward Leigh MP's official site]\n* [http://anothercountry.edwardleigh.org.uk/ Another Country - personal blog containing 'Thoughts from a Christian perspective']\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=sir-edward-leigh/345 |hansardcurr=1455 |hansard=mr-edward-leigh |publicwhip=Edward_Leigh |theywork=edward_leigh}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120908183520/http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/l/1207/Edward+Julian.aspx ''Debrett's People of Today'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051101005248/http://www.parliament.uk/parliamentary_committees/committee_of_public_accounts.cfm Public Accounts Committee]\n*{{C-SPAN|edwardleigh}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Marcus Kimball]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Gainsborough and Horncastle (UK Parliament constituency)|Gainsborough and Horncastle]]\n |years=[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\n}}\n{{s-non|reason=Constituency abolished}}\n|-\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Gainsborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Gainsborough]]\n |years= [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Chair of the Public Accounts Committee]]|years=2001\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Margaret Hodge|Dame Margaret Hodge]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{East Midlands Conservative Party MPs}}\n{{2019 Speaker of the British House of Commons election}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leigh, Edward}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people of Norman descent]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:People educated at The Oratory School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Lyc\u00e9e Fran\u00e7ais Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College, Durham]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Knights of Malta]]\n[[Category:Members of the Greater London Council]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Inner Temple]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Italian civil awards and decorations]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Durham Union]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Sir Edward Leigh\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]] \n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image            = Official portrait of Rt Hon Sir Edward Leigh MP crop 2.jpg\n| office           = [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Chairman of the <br /> Public Accounts Committee]]\n| term_start       = 7 June 2001\n| term_end         = 9 June 2010\n| preceded         = [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]]\n| succeeded        = [[Margaret Hodge|Dame Margaret Hodge]]\n| office1          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Gainsborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Gainsborough]]<br /><small>[[Gainsborough and Horncastle (UK Parliament constituency)|Gainsborough and Horncastle]] (1983\u20131997)</small>\n| majority1        = 22,967 (45.0%)\n| term_start1      = 9 June 1983\n| term_end1        =  \n| predecessor1     = [[Marcus Kimball]]\n| successor1       = \n| birth_name       = Edward Julian Egerton Leigh\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1950|07|20|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Metropolitan Borough of Kensington|Kensington]], [[London]], England\n| spouse           = Mary ''n\u00e9e'' Goodman <br />(''now'' Lady Leigh)\n| party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| children         = 6\n| residence        = London and Lincolnshire\n| alma_mater       = [[Durham University]]\n| occupation       = [[Politician]]\n| profession       = [[Barrister]]\n| website          = [http://www.edwardleigh.org.uk/ www.edwardleigh.org.uk]}}\n\n'''Sir Edward Julian Egerton Leigh''' (born 20 July 1950) is a [[British people|British]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician who has served as a [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] since 1983.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gainsboroughconservatives.org.uk/people/sir-edward-leigh|title=Rt Hon Sir Edward Leigh MP|publisher=Gainsborough Conservatives|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nLeigh has represented [[Gainsborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Gainsborough]], [[Lincolnshire]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] since [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]] (representing its predecessor [[List of United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|constituency]], [[Gainsborough and Horncastle (UK Parliament constituency)|Gainsborough and Horncastle]], until [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]])<ref>{{cite web|publisher=UK Parliament Website|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/edward-leigh/25183|title=Edward Leigh profile|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020192116/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/edward-leigh/25183|archivedate=20 October 2012}}</ref> and has spoken in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliament]] on [[civil liberties]], [[constitutional]], [[ecclesiastical]] and [[economic]] matters.\n\nLeigh was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the [[2013 Birthday Honours|Queen's 2013 Birthday Honours]] for \"public and political service\",<ref name=gaz31712>{{London Gazette|issue=60534 |supp=y |page=1|date=15 June 2013}}</ref><ref name='HM Birthday Honours 2013'>{{cite web | url = https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/206698/Birthday_Honours_List_2013.pdf | title = Birthday Honours List 2013 | accessdate = 14 June 2013 | date = 14 June 2013 | publisher = HM Government}}</ref> and has also received [[honour]]s from the [[French Government|French]] and [[Italian Government]]s.\n\nInitially dubbed \"[[Viscount|the Viscount]]\" in [[Houses of Parliament|parliamentary circles]] alluding to his [[landed gentry]] [[ancestry|background]], Leigh has a reputation at [[Westminster]] for his independence of mind as a \"serial rebeller\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/eureferendum/11973490/David-Cameron-sparks-MPs-protests-in-the-Commons-by-sacking-three-serial-Tory-rebels-from-Europe-body.html|title=David Cameron sparks MPs' protests in the Commons by sacking three 'serial' Tory rebels from Europe body|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=29 July 2017}}</ref> who is prepared to vote against his own [[political party]] if it conflicts with his own principles.<ref name=\"conservativehome.blogs.com\">{{cite web|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/platform/2013/06/edward-leigh-mp.html|title=Sir Edward Leigh MP: After a weak Queen's Speech, we could lose the next election - unless we change course|publisher=}}</ref> He was one of the original [[Maastricht Rebels]] and reportedly got the sack for organising Euro-rebels among ministers.<ref name=\"conservativehome.blogs.com\"/> In 2003 Leigh opposed military intervention in Iraq;<ref name=\"Did your MP support the rebels\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2862397.stm|location=London, UK|work=The BBC|title=Did your MP support the rebels?|date=19 March 2003}}</ref> he has since called for those who voted for the [[Iraq War]], and are still seeking to justify their support for it, to be held to account.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cornerstonegroup.wordpress.com/2016/07/14/on-the-chilcot-report/|title=On the Chilcot Report|last=cornerstonegroup|date=14 July 2016|website=Cornerstone|accessdate=29 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe served as the [[Chairman]] of the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] from 2001 to 2010, investigating government waste and seeking value for money in [[public expenditure]]. Sir Edward stepped down at the end of the [[parliamentary session]] in [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]], it being customary for an [[Her Majesty's Most Loyal Opposition (United Kingdom)|opposition MP]] to hold this post.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fm-world.co.uk/news/fm-industry-news/leigh-to-step-down-as-head-of-pac/|title=Leigh to step down as head of PAC|date=26 October 2009|work=FM World}}</ref>\n\nLeigh has edited and authored three books: ''Right Thinking'' (1988); ''The Nation that forgot God'' (2008);<ref>{{cite book|title=The Nation That Forgot God: A Book of Essays|last=Leigh|first=Edward|date=31 March 2008|publisher=Social Affairs Unit|isbn=9781904863410|editor-last=Haydon|editor-first=Alex|location=London}}</ref> and ''Monastery of the Mind'' (2012).<ref>{{cite book|title=Monastery of the Mind: A Pilgrimage with St Ignatius|last=Leigh|first=Sir Edward|date=31 July 2012|publisher=St Pauls Publishing|isbn=9780854398133}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Knights Bachelor Insignia.png|thumb|left|100px| Insignia of a [[Knight Bachelor]]]]\nLeigh was educated at [[The Oratory School]], the [[Lyc\u00e9e Fran\u00e7ais Charles de Gaulle]] (the French School in London) before going up to [[University College, Durham]], where he read [[History]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]]) and was elected President of the [[Durham Union Society]].\n\nAfter graduating Leigh was [[called to the Bar]] at the [[Inner Temple]] and practised in [[arbitration]] and [[criminal law]] at [[Chambers (law)|Goldsmiths Chambers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldsmithchambers.com/about-us/|title=About Us - Goldsmith Chambers|publisher=}}</ref> He is a [[Fellow]] of the [[Chartered Institute of Arbitrators]] (FCIArb) and formerly served as an [[Ensign (rank)|Ensign]] in the [[Honourable Artillery Company]].<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm130717/debtext/130717-0002.htm#13071772001774 Profile], publications.parliament.uk; accessed 14 July 2015.</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHis father, [[Neville Leigh|Sir Neville Leigh]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCVO}}, hailed from the [[History of Cheshire|ancient Cheshire]] [[Dynasty|family]] of [[High Legh#History|West Hall, High Legh]], a descendant of the [[Egerton family#Earls of Bridgewater (1617)|Egertons, earls of Bridgewater]].\n\nHis maternal grandfather was [[Colonel]] Cyril Denzil Branch {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MC}}, a French citizen, and he is a nephew of [[Russian nobility|Prince]] [[Galitzine|Nikolai Galitzine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://burkespeerage.com/|title=Burke's Peerage - The Official Website|website=burkespeerage.com|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nLeigh first stood for Parliament at the [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974 general election]] when he contested the safe [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] seat of [[Middlesbrough (UK Parliament constituency)|Middlesbrough]], but he was beaten by [[Arthur Bottomley]].\n\nLeigh worked in the private office of [[Margaret Thatcher]] from 1976\u201377 as a political secretary when she was Leader of the Opposition. Leigh was elected to [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames|Richmond Borough Council]] and thereafter to the [[Greater London Council]], serving as [[Councillor]] between 1974 and 1981.\n\nIn 1983, he was returned as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] for Gainsborough and Horncastle. A strong supporter of [[Margaret Thatcher]], Leigh visited [[10 Downing Street]] with fellow MP [[Michael Brown (UK politician)|Michael Brown]] on the morning of Thatcher's resignation as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] in 1990 to try to persuade her to carry on.<ref name=\"Blundell2008\">{{cite book|author=John Blundell|title=Lady Thatcher: A Portrait|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hbyeLS83iEIC&pg=PA163|accessdate=23 November 2012|date=September 2008|publisher=Algora Publishing|isbn=978-0-87586-631-4|pages=162\u2013163}}</ref> Although [[Charles Powell]] advised them it was a forlorn task, they were nonetheless granted access to [[Cabinet (government)|the Cabinet]] which was in process at the time. Leigh and Brown departed 10 Downing Street and walked down [[Whitehall]] back to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] reputedly with \"tears in their eyes\". After Thatcher resigned, in the ensuing leadership election, Leigh supported [[Michael Heseltine]], under whom he had served at the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] (DTI), preferring to support someone who had stabbed Thatcher in the front to those who had stabbed her in the back.<ref name=\"Criddle2012\">{{cite book|author=Byron Criddle|title=Almanac of British Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bDtm2o0m7gIC&pg=PA385|accessdate=23 November 2012|date=10 September 2012|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-26833-2|pages=385}}</ref>\n\nLeigh served as a [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] in [[John Major]]'s [[Major ministry (disambiguation)|ministry]]<!--intentional link to DAB page, 1990-93--> but was sacked in May 1993 over the stance he took by opposing the [[Maastricht Treaty]]. Whilst in office at the DTI he was a keen advocate of [[privatisation]] of the [[Post Office]] (opposed by Labour at the time but as the [[Royal Mail]] division attracting general bipartisan support and floated on the [[London Stock Exchange]] in 2013). In the following [[1995 Conservative Party (UK) leadership election|Conservative leadership election]], Leigh supported [[John Redwood]].<ref name=\"Criddle2012\"/>\n\nFrom 2001 until 2010, Leigh served as [[Chairman]] of the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]], the principal parliamentary body auditing the Budget, investigating government waste and seeking value for money in public expenditure. During his two terms as [[Parliamentary procedure|Chairman]], the PAC took evidence on 420 separate government projects and programmes and was responsible for saving the taxpayer over \u00a34 billion.<ref>'[http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/uk_news/Society/article252950.ece An open letter to my successor as Chair of the Committee of Public Accounts]', by Edward Leigh MP, March 2010</ref>{{better source|reason=This is a statement from Leigh himself |date=September 2019}}\n\nIn October 2006, Leigh was vocal in stating that after [[David Cameron]] had become leader of the party, core supporters were drifting away from voting Conservative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/oct/02/comment.politics|title=Max Hastings: Cameron's big problem - the Conservative party|first=Max|last=Hastings|date=1 October 2006|publisher=}}</ref> Nonetheless, his effective chairmanship of the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] led to the rejuvenation of his parliamentary career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/telegraph-view/10013176/An-artful-game-by-the-taxpayers-champion.html|title=An artful game by the taxpayers' champion|first=|last=|date=23 April 2013|accessdate=31 October 2019|newspaper=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 2008, as Chairman of the PAC, he was embarrassed by relying on flawed [[Department for Transport]] (DfT) statistics to attack motorcyclists for [[tax evasion]]. He accused 38% of motorcyclists of evading [[vehicle excise duty]]. He later apologised for this following the admission by the DfT that 95.5% of motorcycles are entirely legal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7268854.stm|title=MPs apologise for motorbike error|date=28 February 2008|work=BBC News Online|publisher=BBC|accessdate=15 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nLeigh was President of the socially conservative [[Cornerstone Group]] representing the views of over 40 Conservative Members of Parliament and was author of the group's inaugural pamphlet ''Faith, Flag and Family'' in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tory Catholic seeks to return 'faith, flag and family' to heart of party philosophy|url=http://archive.catholicherald.co.uk/article/29th-july-2005/3/tory-catholic-seeks-to-returnfaith-flag-and-family|newspaper=Catholic Herald|date=29 July 2005|accessdate=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 to 2011, Leigh served as an Independent Financial Advisor to [[HM Treasury]], appointed by [[George Osborne]] to bring external challenge to the development and implementation of a new financial management strategy for central government. He stood down in 2011, but was then reappointed to report directly to the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] on improving Parliament's financial scrutiny of the Budget. He was a member of the Treasury Financial Reporting & Advisory Board and, in 2010, Leigh became a delegate to the [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]], speaking regularly and serving on the [[European Parliament Committee on Culture and Education|Culture, Science, Education and Media Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edwardleigh.org.uk/tags/council-of-europe/|title=Council of Europe - Edward Leigh MP - Gainsborough|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of 2010 Leigh was offered but declined the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[ambassadorship]] to the [[Holy See]].<ref>''The Daily Telegraph''. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/religion/8246963/Criticism-as-David-Cameron-sends-trouble-shooter-to-the-Vatican.html Leigh turns down appointment as UK Ambassador to The Vatican]</ref> Leigh also supported [[Boris Johnson]]'s call to [[George Osborne]] in 2011 for lowering the rate of [[taxation]] in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] so as to assist its economic recovery following the [[credit crunch]].<ref>''The Evening Standard'': [http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23918264-boris-johnson-urges-george-osborne-over-lower-taxes.do Leigh joins call for lower taxes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201024842/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23918264-boris-johnson-urges-george-osborne-over-lower-taxes.do |date=1 February 2011 }}</ref> Leigh, a qualified [[barrister]] and an [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe|Assembly Member]] of the [[Council of Europe]],<ref>{{cite web|title=PACE Member File Edward Leigh|url=http://www.assembly.coe.int/nw/xml/AssemblyList/MP-Details-EN.asp?MemberID=6670|website=www.assembly.coe.int|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref> opposes further human rights legislation, as proposed by the [[European Court of Human Rights]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/columnists/charlesmoore/8333820/If-we-want-our-human-rights-then-bring-them-back-home.html# \"If we want our human rights then bring them back home\"], Telegraph.co.uk; accessed 14 July 2015.</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Leigh was appointed [[Chairman]] of the [[Public Accounts Commission]], the body which audits the [[National Audit Office (United Kingdom)|National Audit Office]].\n\nIn 2012, Leigh, together with a record number of fellow Conservative MPs, including numerous [[Privy Counsellor]]s, successfully voted against the [[United Kingdom coalition government (2010\u20132015)|Coalition Government]]'s attempted railroading of [[House of Lords Reform Bill 2012|House of Lords]] [[Lords Reform|Reform]] by limiting time for meaningful parliamentary debate on this major constitutional issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/pm-pledges-one-more-try-at-lords-reform-10476236|title= PM pledges one more try at Lords reform|publisher= news.sky.com|date=11 July 2012|accessdate= 14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Leigh criticised the Government\u2019s decision to allow [[Mitochondrial disease#Management and prevention|mitochondrial replacement therapy]] to prevent the birth of the children with incurable diseases such as muscular dystrophy. These diseases affect up to 1 in 6,500 babies which Leigh stated could lead to people being \u201charvested for their parts\" and a divide between what he referred to as \"the modified and the unmodified\". The [[Department for Health]] asserted no genetic modification is involved.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/11069117/Britain-will-be-considered-a-rogue-state-if-it-creates-GM-people-MP-warns.html|title=Britain will be considered a 'rogue state' if it creates GM people, MP warns|author=Press Association|work=Daily Telegraph|date=1 September 2014|accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande|French President]] appointed him to the [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]] for his role as \u201ca bridge between our parliaments, our governments and our societies\u201d, as stated by [[Sylvie Bermann|H.E. Sylvie Bermann]] at his investiture.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ambafrance-uk.org/Sir-Edward-Leigh-is-made-an-Officier-in-the-Legion-d-Honneur|title=Sir Edward Leigh is made an Officier in the L\u00e9gion d'Honneur|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, he joined three other Conservative MPs in \"talking out\" a Bill introduced by [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] [[Caroline Lucas|Dr Caroline Lucas]], which aimed to reverse moves to privatise the [[NHS]]. By [[filibustering]] for three and a half hours, Lucas was left with just 17 minutes to present her Bill, which was subsequently shelved without a vote.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/nhs-reinstatement-bill-tory-mps-filibuster-debate-by-talking-about-deporting-foreigners-for-hours-a6925781.html NHS Reinstatement Bill: Tory MPs filibuster debate by talking about deporting foreigners for hours]. ''The Independent''. Published 11 March 2016. Retrieved 3 November 2017.</ref>\n\nOne of 21 MPs who, in March 2019, voted against LGBT inclusive sex and relationship education in English schools,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/education/lgbt-sex-relationship-education-mps-support/|title=MPs vote for LGBT inclusive sex and relationship education from primary school|first=Benjamin|last=Butterworth|date=28 March 2019|website=inews.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/21-mps-who-voted-against-14198149|title=21 MPs who voted against teaching kids about gay families|first=Nicola|last=Bartlett|date=28 March 2019|website=mirror}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://commonsvotes.digiminster.com/Divisions/Details/650#noes|title=Draft Relationships Education, Relationships and Sex Education and Health Education (England) Regulations 2019 - CommonsVotes|website=commonsvotes.digiminster.com}}</ref> Leigh was returned with a massive majority at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].<ref>[https://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/news/local-news/general-election-gainsborough-edward-leigh-3638105 www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk]</ref>\n\n===Beliefs===\nLeigh is a [[Roman Catholic]], and maintains a personal blog containing ''Thoughts from a Christian perspective''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://anothercountry.edwardleigh.org.uk/|title=Another Country &#124; Thoughts from a Christian perspective \u2014 by Edward Leigh|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref> He has argued for tightening of [[abortion law]] regarding [[Embryonic stem cell|human embryonic]] [[research]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/mps-throw-out-bids-to-reduce-abortion-limit-831577.html|title=MPs throw out bids to reduce abortion limit|date=20 May 2008|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/10/09/tory-mp-abortion-female-foetus_n_4071551.html|title=The Most Dangerous Position In Britain Today Is... 'To Be A Female Foetus'|date=9 October 2013|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/may/19/health.health|title=Ban on hybrid embryos and saviour siblings fails|first=Andrew|last=Sparrow|date=19 May 2008|publisher=}}</ref> He was on the losing side in defence of [[Section 28]] and opposed the [[Civil Partnership Act 2004]], voting against it in Parliament at its [[Reading (legislature)|Second Reading]]. Leigh later proposed an amendment to extend the property and pension rights afforded by [[civil partnership]]s to siblings who had lived together for more than 12 years. This was opposed by many backers of the initial [[Bill (law)|Bill]], such as fellow Conservative MP [[Alan Duncan|Sir Alan Duncan]], who dubbed it a [[wrecking amendment]].<ref name='ePolitix 2004-11-09'>{{cite web|url=http://www.epolitix.com/latestnews/article-detail/newsarticle/conservatives-split-on-civil-partnerships/?no_cache=1 |title=Conservatives split on civil partnerships |accessdate=13 January 2010 |last=Davie |first=Edward |date=9 November 2004 |publisher=ePolitix.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604180419/http://www.epolitix.com/latestnews/article-detail/newsarticle/conservatives-split-on-civil-partnerships/?no_cache=1 |archivedate=4 June 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name='Changing Attitude'>{{cite web|url=http://www.changingattitude.org.uk/news/newsitem.asp?id=72|title=Civil Partnership bill wrecking amendment defeated|last=Coward|first=Colin|date=9 November 2004|publisher=Changing Attitude|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070607205416/http://www.changingattitude.org.uk/news/newsitem.asp?id=72|archivedate=7 June 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Opposition to Conservative leadership===\nOn a number of occasions Leigh has voted against the leadership of his [[political party|party]] where it conflicts with his personal [[principle]]s.<ref name=\"conservativehome.blogs.com\"/> In 2003, Leigh rebelled against the leadership of his own party and the Labour government to \n[[Opposition to the Iraq War|oppose military intervention in Iraq]] in 2003.<ref name=\"Did your MP support the rebels\"/> He was one of only 15 Conservative rebels who opposed it at the time.\n\nSince the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 European Union Referendum]], Leigh advocates [[Brexit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|title=Which Tory MPs back Brexit, who doesn't and who is still on the fence? - Coffee House|date=16 February 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, the House of Commons overwhelmingly passed an Opposition motion to delay the introduction of [[Universal Credit]] and iron out problems with the system first. Leigh strongly criticised the Government decision to ignore the vote, stating: \"the road to tyranny is paved by executives ignoring parliaments.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/oct/19/were-not-ignoring-you-but-vote-doesnt-bind-pms-deputy-tells-mps We're not ignoring you but vote doesn't bind, PM's deputy tells MPs] ''[[The Guardian]]'' 19 October 2017</ref>\n\n===Speakership elections===\nA veteran [[backbencher]], Leigh was encouraged to run for the [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speakership of the House of Commons]], and after the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] for one of the [[Chairman of Ways and Means|Deputy Speakerships]], but chose not to stand then as [[Constitutional convention (political custom)|parliamentary convention]] was that governing party members were not to be elected to such offices unless already ''[[in situ]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/EdwardLeighMP/status/1121367417509351424|title=When a vacancy occurs I intend to stand for the office of Speaker. I would be a traditional Speaker who does not speak much. Like a judge I would, by my conduct and dress, submerge my personality into the office.|last=MP|first=Sir Edward Leigh|date=25 April 2019|website=@EdwardLeighMP|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lincolnshirelive.co.uk/news/local-news/sir-edward-leigh-reveals-wants-2796354|title=Sir Edward Leigh says he wants to replace Bercow and become Speaker|last=Lodge|first=Matthew|date=25 April 2019|website=lincolnshirelive|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nLeigh ran for the Speakership of the House of Commons in [[2019 Speaker of the British House of Commons election|2019]] after Speaker [[John Bercow]] retired; he stated that, if elected Speaker, he would be fair to all sides and assume a traditional role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/politics/opinion/house-commons/106453/sir-edward-leigh-if-elected-speaker-i-would-submerge|title=Sir Edward Leigh: If elected Speaker, I would submerge my personality into the office and keep business flowing|date=11 September 2019|website=PoliticsHome.com|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref> He was eliminated after receiving 12 votes in the first ballot.\n\n===All-Party Parliamentary Groups===\nFluent in [[French language|French]], Leigh currently serves as Chairman of the [[All-party parliamentary group|All-Party Parliamentary Group]] on [[France]] and the [[All-party parliamentary group|All-Party Parliamentary Group]] on [[Italy]], delivering a speech in [[Italian language|Italian]] at the [[Palace of Westminster]] to visiting [[Chamber of Deputies (Italy)|Deputies of the Italian Parliament]]. He is also the Chairman of the new [[All-party parliamentary group|All-Party Parliamentary Group]] on [[Russia]], Secretary of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on [[Insurance]], and Chairman of the Foreign Affairs, Defence, and International Development subcommittee of the [[1922 Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/sir-edward-leigh/345|title=Rt Hon Sir Edward Leigh MP|website=UK Parliament|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nLeigh was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in [[2013 Birthday Honours|2013]] for \"public and political service\",<ref name=gaz31712/><ref name='HM Birthday Honours 2013'/>\n* [[Image:Knight-Bachelor.ribbon.png|45px]] [[Knight Bachelor]] (2013)\n* [[File:Legion Honneur Officier ribbon.svg|45px]] [[Officer|Officier]] of the [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]] (2015)\n* [[File:StellaItalia-Cav.png|45px]] [[Commander (order)|Commander]] of the [[Order of the Star of Italy]] (2017)\n* [[File:SMOM-gc.svg|45px]] [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Knight of Honour and Devotion]] of the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta]] (1994)\n* [[File:Royal Arms of the United Kingdom (Privy Council).svg|45px]] [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellor]] ([[2019 New Year Honours|2019]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/privy-council-appointments-december-2018|title=Privy Council appointments December 2018|website=GOV.UK}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLeigh married Mary Goodman in London on 25 September 1984 in London; the great granddaughter of [[Duke Georg Alexander of Mecklenburg-Strelitz]] through her mother, and the great-granddaughter of [[Lady Ottoline Morrell]] through her father. She is a direct descendant of [[Catherine II, Empress of Russia]] and [[Princess Augusta of Great Britain]], a sister of [[George III of the United Kingdom|King George III]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britroyals.com/succession.htm|title=Line of Succession to the British Throne|publisher=}}</ref> By marrying a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]], Lady Leigh had previously forfeited her precedence in the [[line of succession to the British throne]] until the [[Succession to the Crown Act 2013|change in the law of 2013]].\n\nSir Edward and Lady Leigh have six children (Natalia, Tamara, Benedict, Marina, Nicholas, and Theodore) and divide their time between homes in [[Westminster]] and in his [[Lincolnshire]] constituency. Their three eldest children work for [[HM Government]] as [[Her Majesty's Civil Service|civil servants]].\n\nLeigh suffers from [[rosacea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm131204/halltext/131204h0001.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 04 Dec 2013 (pt 0001)|website=publications.parliament.uk|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of MPs elected in the 1983 United Kingdom general election]]\n* [[List of Durham University people]]\n* [[:Category:Presidents of the Durham Union|List of Presidents of the Durham Union]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Edward Leigh}}\n* [http://www.edwardleigh.org.uk/ Sir Edward Leigh MP's official site]\n* [http://anothercountry.edwardleigh.org.uk/ Another Country - personal blog containing 'Thoughts from a Christian perspective']\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=sir-edward-leigh/345 |hansardcurr=1455 |hansard=mr-edward-leigh |publicwhip=Edward_Leigh |theywork=edward_leigh}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120908183520/http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/l/1207/Edward+Julian.aspx ''Debrett's People of Today'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051101005248/http://www.parliament.uk/parliamentary_committees/committee_of_public_accounts.cfm Public Accounts Committee]\n*{{C-SPAN|edwardleigh}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Marcus Kimball]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Gainsborough and Horncastle (UK Parliament constituency)|Gainsborough and Horncastle]]\n |years=[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\n}}\n{{s-non|reason=Constituency abolished}}\n|-\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Gainsborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Gainsborough]]\n |years= [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Chair of the Public Accounts Committee]]|years=2001\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Margaret Hodge|Dame Margaret Hodge]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{East Midlands Conservative Party MPs}}\n{{2019 Speaker of the British House of Commons election}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leigh, Edward}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people of Norman descent]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:People educated at The Oratory School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Lyc\u00e9e Fran\u00e7ais Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College, Durham]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Knights of Malta]]\n[[Category:Members of the Greater London Council]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Inner Temple]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Italian civil awards and decorations]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Durham Union]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Leigh"}
{"title_page": "Greg Knight", "text_new": "{{for|the founder and former chief executive of Welbeck Solutions|Greg Knight (businessman)}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Sir Gregory Knight\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Greg knight speaks at meeting.jpg\n| alt =\n| office  = [[Vice-Chamberlain of the Household]]\n| term_start  = 4 September 2012\n| term_end  = 7 October 2013\n| primeminister  = [[David Cameron]]\n| predecessor  = [[Mark Francois]]\n| successor  = [[Desmond Swayne]]\n| office1 = [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Industry]]\n| term_start1 = 23 July 1996\n| term_end1 = 2 May 1997\n| primeminister1 = [[John Major]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Timothy Eggar]]\n| successor1 = [[John Battle (politician)|John Battle]]\n| office2 = [[Chief Whip|Government Deputy Chief Whip<br />in the House of Commons]]<br />[[Treasurer of the Household]]\n| term_start2 = 7 June 1993\n| term_end2 = 23 July 1996\n| primeminister2 = [[John Major]]\n| predecessor2 = [[David Heathcoat-Amory]]\n| successor2 = [[Andrew MacKay]]\n| office3 = [[Lords of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Margaret Thatcher]]<br />[[John Major]]\n| term_start3 = 25 July 1990\n| term_end3 = 27 May 1993\n| predecessor3 = [[Michael Fallon]]\n| successor3 = [[Andrew MacKay]]\n| office4 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[East Yorkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Yorkshire]]\n| majority4 = 22,787 (43.2%)\n| predecessor4 = [[John Townend]]\n| successor4 = \n| term_start4 = 7 June 2001\n| term_end4 = \n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Derby North (UK Parliament constituency)|Derby North]]\n| predecessor5 = [[Philip Whitehead]]\n| successor5 = [[Bob Laxton]]\n| term_start5 = 9 June 1983\n| term_end5 = 1 May 1997\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1949|4|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Blaby (district)|Blaby]], [[Leicestershire]], England\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Janet Ormond<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.driffieldintouch.com/news/126/ |title=Siedmere event hailed a success \u2013 \"also enjoying the evening were the Rt Hon Greg Knight, MP, his wife Janet\" |publisher=driffieldintouch.com |accessdate=9 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110421000243/http://www.driffieldintouch.com/news/126/ |archivedate=21 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = [[University of Law|The College of Law]]\n| occupation =\n| profession = Solicitor\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website = [http://www.gregknight.com/ www.gregknight.com]\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Sir Gregory Knight''' (born 4 April 1949) is a British politician, author and musician. He serves as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP for [[East Yorkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Yorkshire]].\n\n==Education and professional life==\n\nBorn in [[Blaby (district)|Blaby]], Leicestershire, Knight was educated at [[Alderman Newton's School|Alderman Newton's Grammar School]], [[Leicester]], and the College of Law Guildford, qualifying as a solicitor in 1973.\n\n==Political career==\nKnight served as a Leicester City Councillor for Castle Ward and Leicestershire County Councillor for Evington Division from 1976 to 1981.\n\nHe was MP for [[Derby North (UK Parliament constituency)|Derby North]] from 1983 until the 1997 election, when he lost his seat. He returned to the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] in 2001 after successfully contesting the [[East Yorkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Yorkshire]] seat.\n\nAs a backbencher, in the 1980s, he succeeded in amending licensing law in England and Wales by doubling 'drinking up time' on licensed premises from ten to twenty minutes, a concession that was welcomed by the industry and drinkers alike. However the 2003 Licensing Act ended standard permitted hours and provides for an unspecified drinking up time determined by the licensee's discretion.\n\nHe is in favour of bringing back capital punishment and spoke out against the [[Apartheid]] government of South Africa during the 1980s.\n\nHe was deputy [[Chief Whip]] under [[John Major]] between 1993 and 1996 and [[Minister of State]] for Industry at the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] from 1996 until the Conservative defeat at the 1997 election. He was made a [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Councillor]] in 1995, entitling him to the style \"Right Honourable\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/privy-council/privy-council-members/privy-counsellors/#k|title=Privy Counsellors|publisher=Privy Council Office|accessdate=12 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111221115352/http://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/privy-council/privy-council-members/privy-counsellors/#k|archive-date=21 December 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe served under [[Michael Howard]] as a shadow minister for Environment and Transport until 2005. In the 2005\u201310 Parliament, he was Chairman of the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] [[Procedure Committee]] and on four other House of Commons select committees: the [[Liaison Committee]], [[Administration Committee]], the [[Select Committee on the Modernisation of the House of Commons|Committee on Modernisation of the House]] and the [[Standards and Privileges Committee]]. He was re-elected unopposed to the chair of the Procedure Committee in 2010.\n\nHe has successfully piloted two of his Private Members Bills into law.  In 2011, he was successful in taking through Parliament the [[Estates of Deceased Persons (Forfeiture Rule and Law of Succession) Act 2011]], a bill to make the distribution of estates fairer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm110304/debtext/110304-0001.htm#11030451000004|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 04 Mar 2011 (pt 0001)|work=Hansard|publisher = UK Parliament |accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe rejoined the government in September 2012 as a Senior Whip and Vice Chamberlain of the Royal Household, a position he held until October 2013.\n\nIn 2018 he introduced his second Private Members Bill, the Parking (Code of Practice) Bill, which mandates the Government to introduce a statutory code of practice for the operators of private car parks, to require transparency and good practice to ensure that motorists are not treated unreasonably. The Bill was passed by Parliament and became an Act in March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://services.parliament.uk/bills/2017-19/parkingcodeofpractice.html|title=Parking (Code of Practice) Act 2019|year=2019|website=www.parliament.uk|accessdate=28 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nKnight strongly supports amending the smoking ban in pubs.<ref name=\"nanny\">{{cite web|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/platform/2009/07/shane-frith-why-you-should-support-the-campaign-to-amend-the-smoking-ban-.html|title=Shane Frith: Why you should support the campaign to amend the smoking ban|work=ConservativeHome|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref> He is a [[Eurosceptic]] and is in favour of Britain leaving the EU.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35616946|title=EU vote: Where the cabinet and other MPs stand|date=2016-06-22|access-date=2019-12-21|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nKnight has argued in Parliament for \"double summertime\", which would see the clocks go forward by two hours during summer.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Rob|title=Time for debate? Don't forget the clocks go back overnight... but should they?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/time-for-debate-dont-forget-the-clocks-go-back-overnight-but-should-they-8904258.html|accessdate=26 March 2015|work=The Independent|date=26 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe is Secretary of the British American Parliamentary Group, one of the largest and most active all-party groups at Westminster.\nAn avid motorist, he is critical of initiatives seen as 'anti-car', such as congestion charging, pedestrianisation schemes, speed humps and some 'park and ride' proposals. He is Chairman of the All-Party Parliamentary Historic Vehicles Group <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historicvehicles.org.uk/|publisher=Parliamentary Historic Vehicles Group|title=Officers|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref> and successfully called on the Government to exempt historic vehicles from [[MOT test]]s.<ref>[http://gregknight.com/2011/11/knight-welcomes-mot-exemption-review/ GregKnight.com]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103045636/http://gregknight.com/2011/11/knight-welcomes-mot-exemption-review/ |date=3 January 2013 }}</ref> In 2007, he was named as one of the 50 most influential people worldwide in the Historic Vehicle Movement.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} In 2011 he was shortlisted as the \u2018Industry Champion of the Year\u2019 by the International Historic Motoring Awards, for his work in supporting the historic and classic car movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historicmotoringawards.com/categories.php?category=company&page=shortlist|title=Category|work=International Historic Motoring Awards|accessdate=12 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402195454/http://historicmotoringawards.com/categories.php?category=company&page=shortlist|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reported that Knight had claimed \u00a32,600 in expenses for \"driveway repairs\" at his constituency home, though Knight stated that his cars were kept separately and paid for out of his own pocket.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jamieson|first1=Alistair|title=Greg Knight: MP's driveway repairs on expenses|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5336317/Greg-Knight-MPs-driveway-repairs-on-expenses.html|accessdate=26 March 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=17 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKnight is a classic car enthusiast and owns a number of classic cars.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nHe plays the drums and is a founder member of [[MP4 (band)|MP4]]<ref name=\"MP4\">{{cite web|url=http://mp4theband.co.uk|title=MP4 The Band|work=MP4|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref>\u2014the world's only parliamentary rock group. The others are fellow MPs [[Kevin Brennan (politician)|Kevin Brennan]] and [[Pete Wishart|Peter Wishart]] and former MP [[Ian Cawsey]].\n\nKnight has backed several other artists on the drums in live shows including [[George McCrae]] (\"[[Rock Your Baby]]\") and [[Fergal Sharkey]] (\"[[Teenage Kicks]]\")<ref>[http://www.gregknight.com/mp4news.php GregKnight.com]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110205050819/http://www.gregknight.com/mp4news.php |date=5 February 2011 }}</ref> and, in the studio, he played drums backing [[KT Tunstall]], [[Steve Harley]], [[Ricky Wilson (singer)|Ricky Wilson]] and [[David Gray (musician)|David Gray]] on the charity single \"[[You Can't Always Get What You Want]]\" released in December 2016 by [[Chrysalis Records]].<ref>[http://www.gregknight.com/1january2011.php GregKnight.com]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110123014518/http://www.gregknight.com/1january2011.php |date=23 January 2011 }}</ref>\n\nHe has written six books, mostly on the subject of political quips and insults.\n\n==Honours==\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} In 1995, he was sworn in as a member of [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council]]. This gave him the [[Honorific|Honorific Title]] \"[[The Right Honourable]]\" for life.\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} In October 2013, he was awarded a [[Knight Bachelor|Knighthood]] for political service. This gave him the [[Honorific|Honorific Title]] \"[[Sir]]\" for life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/knighthoods-conferred-greg-knight-mp-and-john-randall-mp|title=Knighthoods conferred: Greg Knight MP and John Randall MP|work=GOV.UK|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*''Westminster Words'' (1988), published by Buchan and Enright\n*''Honourable Insults'' (1990), published by Robson Books\n*''Parliamentary Sauce'' (1993), published by Robson Books\n*''Right Honourable Insults'' (1998), published by Chrysalis Books\n*''Naughty Graffiti'' (2005), published by Anova Books\n*''Dishonourable Insults'' (2011), published by The Robson Press ({{ISBN|9781849541619}})\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gregknight.com gregknight.com]\n* {{UK MP links | parliament = sir-greg-knight/1200 |hansardcurr = 1343 | hansard = mr-greg-knight | publicwhip = greg_knight | theywork = greg_knight}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[Philip Whitehead]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title=Member of Parliament for [[Derby North (UK Parliament constituency)|Derby North]] |years=[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Bob Laxton]]}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[John Townend]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title=Member of Parliament for [[East Yorkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Yorkshire]] |years=[[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[David Heathcoat-Amory]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Treasurer of the Household]] |years=1993\u20131996}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Andrew MacKay]]}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[Mark Francois]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Vice-Chamberlain of the Household]] |years=2012\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Yorkshire and the Humber Conservative Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knight, Gregory}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Blaby]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Politics of the East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for constituencies in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Alderman Newton's School, Leicester]]\n[[Category:Treasurers of the Household]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) councillors]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Leicestershire]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the founder and former chief executive of Welbeck Solutions|Greg Knight (businessman)}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Sir Gregory Knight\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Greg knight speaks at meeting.jpg\n| alt =\n| office  = [[Vice-Chamberlain of the Household]]\n| term_start  = 4 September 2012\n| term_end  = 7 October 2013\n| primeminister  = [[David Cameron]]\n| predecessor  = [[Mark Francois]]\n| successor  = [[Desmond Swayne]]\n| office1 = [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Industry]]\n| term_start1 = 23 July 1996\n| term_end1 = 2 May 1997\n| primeminister1 = [[John Major]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Timothy Eggar]]\n| successor1 = [[John Battle (politician)|John Battle]]\n| office2 = [[Chief Whip|Government Deputy Chief Whip<br />in the House of Commons]]<br />[[Treasurer of the Household]]\n| term_start2 = 7 June 1993\n| term_end2 = 23 July 1996\n| primeminister2 = [[John Major]]\n| predecessor2 = [[David Heathcoat-Amory]]\n| successor2 = [[Andrew MacKay]]\n| office3 = [[Lords of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Margaret Thatcher]]<br />[[John Major]]\n| term_start3 = 25 July 1990\n| term_end3 = 27 May 1993\n| predecessor3 = [[Michael Fallon]]\n| successor3 = [[Andrew MacKay]]\n| office4 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[East Yorkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Yorkshire]]\n| majority4 = 22,787 (43.2%)\n| predecessor4 = [[John Townend]]\n| successor4 = \n| term_start4 = 7 June 2001\n| term_end4 = \n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Derby North (UK Parliament constituency)|Derby North]]\n| predecessor5 = [[Philip Whitehead]]\n| successor5 = [[Bob Laxton]]\n| term_start5 = 9 June 1983\n| term_end5 = 1 May 1997\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1949|4|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Blaby (district)|Blaby]], [[Leicestershire]], England\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Janet Ormond<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.driffieldintouch.com/news/126/ |title=Siedmere event hailed a success \u2013 \"also enjoying the evening were the Rt Hon Greg Knight, MP, his wife Janet\" |publisher=driffieldintouch.com |accessdate=9 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110421000243/http://www.driffieldintouch.com/news/126/ |archivedate=21 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = [[University of Law|The College of Law]]\n| occupation =\n| profession = Solicitor\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website = [http://www.gregknight.com/ www.gregknight.com]\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Sir Gregory Knight''' (born 4 April 1949) is a British politician, author and musician. He serves as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP for [[East Yorkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Yorkshire]].\n\n==Education and professional life==\n\nBorn in [[Blaby (district)|Blaby]], Leicestershire, Knight was educated at [[Alderman Newton's School|Alderman Newton\u2019s Grammar School]], [[Leicester]], and the College of Law Guildford, qualifying as a solicitor in 1973.\n\n==Political career==\nKnight served as a Leicester City Councillor for Castle Ward and Leicestershire County Councillor for Evington Division from 1976 to 1981.\n\nHe was MP for [[Derby North (UK Parliament constituency)|Derby North]] from 1983 until the 1997 election, when he lost his seat. He returned to the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] in 2001 after successfully contesting the [[East Yorkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|East Yorkshire]] seat.\n\nAs a backbencher, in the 1980s, he succeeded in amending licensing law in England and Wales by doubling 'drinking up time' on licensed premises from ten to twenty minutes, a concession that was welcomed by the industry and drinkers alike. However the 2003 Licensing Act ended standard permitted hours and provides for an unspecified drinking up time determined by the licensee\u2019s discretion.\n\nHe is in favour of bringing back capital punishment and spoke out against the [[Apartheid]] government of South Africa during the 1980s.\n\nHe was deputy [[Chief Whip]] under [[John Major]] between 1993 and 1996 and [[Minister of State]] for Industry at the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] from 1996 until the Conservative defeat at the 1997 election. He was made a [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Councillor]] in 1995, entitling him to the style \"Right Honourable\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/privy-council/privy-council-members/privy-counsellors/#k|title=Privy Counsellors|publisher=Privy Council Office|accessdate=12 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111221115352/http://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/privy-council/privy-council-members/privy-counsellors/#k|archive-date=21 December 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe served under [[Michael Howard]] as a shadow minister for Environment and Transport until 2005. In the 2005\u201310 Parliament, he was Chairman of the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] [[Procedure Committee]] and on four other House of Commons select committees: the [[Liaison Committee]], [[Administration Committee]], the [[Select Committee on the Modernisation of the House of Commons|Committee on Modernisation of the House]] and the [[Standards and Privileges Committee]]. He was re-elected unopposed to the chair of the Procedure Committee in 2010.\n\nHe has successfully piloted two of his Private Members Bills into law.  In 2011, he was successful in taking through Parliament the [[Estates of Deceased Persons (Forfeiture Rule and Law of Succession) Act 2011]], a bill to make the distribution of estates fairer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm110304/debtext/110304-0001.htm#11030451000004|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 04 Mar 2011 (pt 0001)|work=Hansard|publisher = UK Parliament |accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe rejoined the government in September 2012 as a Senior Whip and Vice Chamberlain of the Royal Household, a position he held until October 2013.\n\nIn 2018 he introduced his second Private Members Bill, the Parking (Code of Practice) Bill, which mandates the Government to introduce a statutory code of practice for the operators of private car parks, to require transparency and good practice to ensure that motorists are not treated unreasonably. The Bill was passed by Parliament and became an Act in March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://services.parliament.uk/bills/2017-19/parkingcodeofpractice.html|title=Parking (Code of Practice) Act 2019|year=2019|website=www.parliament.uk|accessdate=28 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nKnight strongly supports amending the smoking ban in pubs.<ref name=\"nanny\">{{cite web|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/platform/2009/07/shane-frith-why-you-should-support-the-campaign-to-amend-the-smoking-ban-.html|title=Shane Frith: Why you should support the campaign to amend the smoking ban|work=ConservativeHome|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref> He is a [[Eurosceptic]] and is in favour of Britain leaving the EU.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35616946|title=EU vote: Where the cabinet and other MPs stand|date=2016-06-22|access-date=2019-12-21|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nKnight has argued in Parliament for \"double summertime\", which would see the clocks go forward by two hours during summer.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Rob|title=Time for debate? Don't forget the clocks go back overnight... but should they?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/time-for-debate-dont-forget-the-clocks-go-back-overnight-but-should-they-8904258.html|accessdate=26 March 2015|work=The Independent|date=26 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe is Secretary of the British American Parliamentary Group, one of the largest and most active all-party groups at Westminster.\nAn avid motorist, he is critical of initiatives seen as 'anti-car', such as congestion charging, pedestrianisation schemes, speed humps and some 'park and ride' proposals. He is Chairman of the All-Party Parliamentary Historic Vehicles Group <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historicvehicles.org.uk/|publisher=Parliamentary Historic Vehicles Group|title=Officers|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref> and successfully called on the Government to exempt historic vehicles from [[MOT test]]s.<ref>[http://gregknight.com/2011/11/knight-welcomes-mot-exemption-review/ GregKnight.com]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103045636/http://gregknight.com/2011/11/knight-welcomes-mot-exemption-review/ |date=3 January 2013 }}</ref> In 2007, he was named as one of the 50 most influential people worldwide in the Historic Vehicle Movement.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} In 2011 he was shortlisted as the \u2018Industry Champion of the Year\u2019 by the International Historic Motoring Awards, for his work in supporting the historic and classic car movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historicmotoringawards.com/categories.php?category=company&page=shortlist|title=Category|work=International Historic Motoring Awards|accessdate=12 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402195454/http://historicmotoringawards.com/categories.php?category=company&page=shortlist|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reported that Knight had claimed \u00a32,600 in expenses for \"driveway repairs\" at his constituency home, though Knight stated that his cars were kept separately and paid for out of his own pocket.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jamieson|first1=Alistair|title=Greg Knight: MP's driveway repairs on expenses|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/5336317/Greg-Knight-MPs-driveway-repairs-on-expenses.html|accessdate=26 March 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=17 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKnight is a classic car enthusiast and owns a number of classic cars.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nHe plays the drums and is a founder member of [[MP4 (band)|MP4]]<ref name=\"MP4\">{{cite web|url=http://mp4theband.co.uk|title=MP4 The Band|work=MP4|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref>\u2014the world's only parliamentary rock group. The others are fellow MPs [[Kevin Brennan (politician)|Kevin Brennan]] and [[Pete Wishart|Peter Wishart]] and former MP [[Ian Cawsey]].\n\nKnight has backed several other artists on the drums in live shows including [[George McCrae]] (\"[[Rock Your Baby]]\") and [[Fergal Sharkey]] (\"[[Teenage Kicks]]\")<ref>[http://www.gregknight.com/mp4news.php GregKnight.com]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110205050819/http://www.gregknight.com/mp4news.php |date=5 February 2011 }}</ref> and, in the studio, he played drums backing [[KT Tunstall]], [[Steve Harley]], [[Ricky Wilson (singer)|Ricky Wilson]] and [[David Gray (musician)|David Gray]] on the charity single \"[[You Can't Always Get What You Want]]\" released in December 2016 by [[Chrysalis Records]].<ref>[http://www.gregknight.com/1january2011.php GregKnight.com]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110123014518/http://www.gregknight.com/1january2011.php |date=23 January 2011 }}</ref>\n\nHe has written six books, mostly on the subject of political quips and insults.\n\n==Honours==\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} In 1995, he was sworn in as a member of [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council]]. This gave him the [[Honorific|Honorific Title]] \"[[The Right Honourable]]\" for life.\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} In October 2013, he was awarded a [[Knight Bachelor|Knighthood]] for political service. This gave him the [[Honorific|Honorific Title]] \"[[Sir]]\" for life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/knighthoods-conferred-greg-knight-mp-and-john-randall-mp|title=Knighthoods conferred: Greg Knight MP and John Randall MP|work=GOV.UK|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*''Westminster Words'' (1988), published by Buchan and Enright\n*''Honourable Insults'' (1990), published by Robson Books\n*''Parliamentary Sauce'' (1993), published by Robson Books\n*''Right Honourable Insults'' (1998), published by Chrysalis Books\n*''Naughty Graffiti'' (2005), published by Anova Books\n*''Dishonourable Insults'' (2011), published by The Robson Press ({{ISBN|9781849541619}})\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gregknight.com gregknight.com]\n* {{UK MP links | parliament = sir-greg-knight/1200 |hansardcurr = 1343 | hansard = mr-greg-knight | publicwhip = greg_knight | theywork = greg_knight}}\n